00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.470
- So thank you, John.

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:19.190
So in today's panel, we're
very excited here to tell you

00:01:19.190 --> 00:01:22.290
a little bit about how the
oceans shape our climate.

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:25.250
And since the early
history of the Earth,

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:27.670
I would say the oceans
really have defined

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:30.410
the climate on this Earth.

00:01:30.410 --> 00:01:33.680
We have seen that the inception
of life, the evolution of life

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:34.940
happened on the ocean.

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:38.700
But also, the oceans regulate
the atmospheric carbon dioxide

00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:40.010
and oxygen.

00:01:40.010 --> 00:01:43.130
And the oceans contain,
for that matter,

00:01:43.130 --> 00:01:45.410
a very large percentage
of the Earth's water,

00:01:45.410 --> 00:01:48.950
97% of the Earth's
water is in the oceans.

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:52.960
Just about 0.001% of the
water is in the atmosphere,

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:54.820
just to give you an idea.

00:01:54.820 --> 00:01:59.500
The oceans contain 98%
of the carbon dioxide,

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:01.520
in dissolved form, of course.

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:04.100
So when we say that
atmospheric carbon dioxide is

00:02:04.100 --> 00:02:06.210
going up or going down,
you have to realize

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:08.770
that there's a lot in
the oceans and the oceans

00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:12.670
have, in the past, regulated
the atmospheric carbon dioxide

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:14.000
very well.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:15.930
Whether they can do
that in the future

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:19.040
is something that
we are still asking.

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:21.540
And the oceans-- you know,
if you think about heat,

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:26.140
where is all the heat, most
of the heat, 90% of the heat,

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:27.730
is in the oceans.

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:31.280
So in many ways, the
oceans define the climate.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:34.510
The circulation of the
oceans defines the climate.

00:02:34.510 --> 00:02:38.550
And about half the primary
production on the Earth

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:42.930
takes place in the oceans.

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:47.320
And we see that the
oceans are constantly

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:49.500
in a state of motion.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:52.610
These ocean currents,
they transport heat

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:53.470
across the oceans.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:54.860
They transport salt.

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.030
And in the very
fundamental way, the oceans

00:02:57.030 --> 00:02:58.610
are different from
the atmosphere.

00:02:58.610 --> 00:03:01.610
One is that they have
enormous heat capacity.

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:04.330
But the atmosphere
is heated from below.

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:07.670
And so the energy of the sun
is what drives the atmosphere.

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:12.150
Whereas the oceans, when
you heat them by the sun,

00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.045
in fact, it's
stratifies the oceans,

00:03:14.045 --> 00:03:15.890
or it creates a
density contrast,

00:03:15.890 --> 00:03:17.890
because warmer
water doesn't sink.

00:03:17.890 --> 00:03:20.470
So in fact, you
see that the winds

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:23.860
are what drive the
ocean to a large extent.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:26.390
And mixing or
overturning the oceans

00:03:26.390 --> 00:03:29.640
is, in fact, very
difficult, because the sun

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:30.960
warms the oceans.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:34.520
So in a nutshell, that
tells you that it's

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:37.630
difficult to communicate
changes through the oceans.

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:40.990
But the oceans really
support a large part

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:43.400
of our primary production
on this planet.

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:45.860
And so about half that
primary production

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:48.360
takes place in the oceans.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:50.010
And that organic
matter, as we have

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:53.040
seen in some of the previous
talks, it sinks very gradually.

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:55.940
Some of it get sequestered,
that carbon to the oceans.

00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:58.090
So the big perturbation
that we've made,

00:03:58.090 --> 00:03:59.750
that humankind has
made, is that we

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:03.810
have taken out that
organic carbon that's

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:05.750
fossilized for millions
and millions of years.

00:04:05.750 --> 00:04:09.050
We have very abruptly brought
it out into the atmosphere.

00:04:09.050 --> 00:04:11.480
And we have created
huge changes.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:14.720
And I have to say that
the ocean has buffered,

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:16.730
is buffering, a
lot of that change

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:19.029
that we might see because
of those abrupt changes.

00:04:19.029 --> 00:04:21.920
A third of the CO2 that we
put out in the atmosphere

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:23.300
has gone into the oceans.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.410
And when we talk
about global warming,

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:28.120
and if you were to ask,
where is all that heat that

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:29.570
has to do with
global warming, why

00:04:29.570 --> 00:04:31.720
is it that we don't
feel very warm today,

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:35.110
it's because 90% of that
heat is in the oceans.

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:39.310
So I'm really excited today
to have this panel here.

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:41.610
We have here three
oceanographers

00:04:41.610 --> 00:04:44.550
whom I really admire,
whose work I really admire.

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:48.050
Maureen Raymo from the
Lamont-Doherty Earth

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:49.720
Observatory at Columbia.

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:53.750
And she has worked on the
past climate of the Earth.

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:55.880
And her work has
shown how important it

00:04:55.880 --> 00:05:00.110
is to think about past climates,
and how past climates help

00:05:00.110 --> 00:05:03.195
us understand the changes that
we're going to go through now,

00:05:03.195 --> 00:05:05.810
or we're going
through at present.

00:05:05.810 --> 00:05:08.660
That's because we have a very
short observational window

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:11.760
in these last few decades.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.410
And so understanding past
climate is really important.

00:05:14.410 --> 00:05:16.000
And then we have
Rebecca Woodgate,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.490
who is an arctic oceanographer.

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:20.380
And she's done a lot of
observations in the Arctic.

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:22.170
And she's really pushed
our understanding

00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:25.090
of how sea ice and
the oceans interact.

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:27.470
And the big changes that
are occurring in the Arctic,

00:05:27.470 --> 00:05:30.300
it's one of the most vulnerable
regions in the oceans because

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:32.920
of the sea ice and the
interaction with the oceans.

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:35.320
And then we have
Lynne Talley, who

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:38.890
has been instrumental in
understanding the large scale

00:05:38.890 --> 00:05:41.190
distribution of
temperature, salt,

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:43.360
and the global
circulation of the oceans.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:46.740
How these things get conveyed
and transported across

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:48.510
the oceans, what
are the changes?

00:05:48.510 --> 00:05:50.850
And she's been
instrumental in some

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:54.170
of the very big ocean
observing programs

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:56.440
that have global and
international programs.

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:58.850
And her understanding
of the global oceans

00:05:58.850 --> 00:06:01.420
through those
programs has really

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:03.640
changed a lot of
our understanding

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:04.990
as oceanographers.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:08.526
So it gives me enormous pleasure
to have these three people here

00:06:08.526 --> 00:06:09.025
today.

00:06:09.025 --> 00:06:12.860
I don't want you to go away
thinking that oceanographers

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:18.000
are necessarily women, but some
of the best oceanographers are.

