00:06:49.210 --> 00:06:52.890
So I've spent most of my career
studying past climate change.

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:57.600
And most of the last five to 10
years studying sea level as it

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:01.370
relates to the past history
of the polar ice sheets.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:05.600
And today, there's two
major polar ice sheets.

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:08.740
There's the one in Greenland,
which if you, hypothetically,

00:07:08.740 --> 00:07:11.120
could melt it all and
spread it in a single layer

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:14.080
over the ocean, sea
level would rise

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:17.210
by about six meters or 20 feet.

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:20.800
And then in the
South Pole, there's

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:22.877
the West Antarctic
ice sheet over here,

00:07:22.877 --> 00:07:25.210
which again, is about the
same size as the Greenland ice

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:25.710
sheet.

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:28.570
And then the much larger
East Antarctic ice sheet,

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:32.240
which you have to go
back 40 million years

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.450
to find a time when that
whole ice sheet had melted.

00:07:34.450 --> 00:07:39.900
And at that time, sea level
was about 180 feet higher

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:40.780
than today.

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:43.270
So the question
I'll just pose here

00:07:43.270 --> 00:07:45.420
is, how sensitive
are these ice sheets

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:46.790
to a modest global warming?

00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:49.270
And by modest, I mean,
let's say one degree

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:52.730
Celsius warmer than today.

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:55.320
I actually know a little
bit about a time period

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.200
that is widely
agreed to have been

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:00.310
two to three degrees
warmer than pre-industrial,

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:03.780
which would be one to two
degrees warmer than today.

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:07.570
And at that time, geochemists,
using various methods,

00:08:07.570 --> 00:08:09.920
have reconstructed
atmospheric CO2.

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:13.610
It is about 400 PPM,
which I know at least some

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:16.060
of the people in the room I
recognize know that's exactly

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:17.020
what it is today.

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:20.720
It's about 401 this week, PPM.

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.350
It should be 280 PPM, but
we'll come back to that.

00:08:25.350 --> 00:08:28.000
And what I'm showing
here is a site

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.600
on the north coast
of Ellesmere Island,

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:33.380
and an artist's
reconstruction based

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:35.400
on the fossils, and
plants, and animals,

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:38.909
and pollen that have been
taken out of that dig

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:41.159
show a reconstruction
of what the north

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:43.190
coast of Greenland
and Canada looked

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:44.980
like three million years ago.

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:47.940
The Greenland ice
sheet did not exist.

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:48.680
OK.

00:08:48.680 --> 00:08:50.790
So climate is
changing all the time.

00:08:50.790 --> 00:08:53.570
Even more recently, there's been
a profound change in climate.

00:08:53.570 --> 00:08:56.610
This is 21,000 years
ago, very recently.

00:08:56.610 --> 00:08:58.290
And obviously, the
Greenland ice sheet

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:02.290
has jumped the Davis Strait and
has expanded dramatically down

00:09:02.290 --> 00:09:05.110
over North America
and Fennoscandia.

00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:08.330
I don't know if this is a big
Game of Thrones crowd in here,

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:12.790
but if the people that like
it will appreciate this quote.

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:15.260
So that is the height
of the ice sheet

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:20.360
over Boston at the peak
of the last ice age.

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:21.060
OK.

00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:25.430
So that was just a blink
of time ago, obviously.

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:30.400
So why do these changes happen?

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:33.100
The climate system is
infinitely complicated.

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:35.660
And there's no
scientist on our planet

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:40.600
that can be an expert in every
part of the climate system.

00:09:40.600 --> 00:09:43.910
But at the same time,
it's somewhat very simple.

00:09:43.910 --> 00:09:48.540
And you can go to the radiation
chapter in a freshman physics

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:50.590
book and see a very
simple equation

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:53.290
to calculate the effect of
temperature of the Earth.

00:09:53.290 --> 00:09:55.130
We don't need that, but
all you need to know

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:55.980
is it's very simple.

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:58.480
And the surface
temperature of the Earth

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:00.140
just adds one more
variable, which

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:02.740
is the concentration
of greenhouse gases.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:04.240
And so I like to
think about it when

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:06.160
I talk to general
audiences, just say, look,

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:08.020
the Earth's climate,
the temperature

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:10.050
of the Earth-- we're
a ball of rock.

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:15.920
We get heated by this star
that's a distance away-- which

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:18.720
I don't know-- one light year?

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:20.980
I don't know.

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:23.210
And there's three
variables that control

00:10:23.210 --> 00:10:24.210
the Earth's temperature.

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:26.430
How close we are to
the sun-- and that

00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:28.400
actually varies
subtly through time

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:31.890
because our orbit isn't
perfectly circular,

00:10:31.890 --> 00:10:35.010
and other large planets
perturb our orbit,

00:10:35.010 --> 00:10:38.380
like Jupiter and
Saturn, on time scales

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:41.530
of tens to hundreds of thousands
of years in very predictable

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:43.960
ways that can be calculated.

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.080
And sometimes, over
billions of years,

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:48.820
the solar output of
the sun can change.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.930
But on human time scales,
it's essentially constant,

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:54.430
which is why we call
it solar constant.

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:57.100
So that's one big knob
you can change that can

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:58.920
control Earth's temperature.

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:01.630
The other is the Earth's
albedo or reflectivity.

00:11:01.630 --> 00:11:05.810
If you expand the snow and ice
coverage at high latitudes,

00:11:05.810 --> 00:11:07.470
you make the Earth
more reflective.

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:09.060
And so more of the
solar radiation

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:10.980
is just lost to space.

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:12.150
It's reflected to space.

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:13.840
It's not available for heating.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.670
I'm sure we'll hear a lot more
about that in the Arctic talk.

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:20.300
And then, finally, we have this
thing called greenhouse gases.

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:23.850
And so we have all this
heat coming in from the sun.

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:26.000
It's warming the
Earth's surface.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.080
The Earth's surface is
cooler than the sun,

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.070
so it re-radiates outward
at longer wavelengths.

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:34.130
And it just happens to interfere
with the molecular structure

00:11:34.130 --> 00:11:36.840
of certain gases,
especially CO2, which

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:38.490
can prevent it from escaping.

00:11:38.490 --> 00:11:41.250
And then re-radiates
it back to the surface.

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.810
So just like throwing more
blankets on on a cold winter

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:45.570
night.

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:47.330
So these are the three knobs.

00:11:47.330 --> 00:11:50.040
And everything I know about
every climate change that

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:52.010
has happened in
the past-- and this

00:11:52.010 --> 00:11:54.370
I will show you-- can
be explained by just

00:11:54.370 --> 00:11:56.730
changing these three variables.

00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:59.158
And I'm going to
show you a model.

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.790
This is the climate model with
an ice sheet embedded in it.

00:12:04.790 --> 00:12:07.890
And it's the last 400,000 years.

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:10.020
This is a sea level scale.

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:13.880
And this is what the climate
for the last 400 years

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:16.740
has looked like, just
the only variables

00:12:16.740 --> 00:12:20.536
being our variable
orbit around the sun,

00:12:20.536 --> 00:12:21.910
changes in the
Earth's precession

00:12:21.910 --> 00:12:25.620
and tilt of the Earth's
axis, and the CO2

00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:28.440
changes that we know
occurred from ice cores.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:31.790
And it actually-- this
is a model result,

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:35.870
but it looks remarkably like
what we know climate did.

00:12:35.870 --> 00:12:36.970
Want to see that again?

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:38.850
- Yeah.

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:41.990
- I could watch it all day.

00:12:41.990 --> 00:12:46.920
This is a paper we published in
Nature by Ayako Abe-Ouchi, who

00:12:46.920 --> 00:12:49.250
is actually the only
female scientist I've ever

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:50.580
met in my field from Japan.

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:55.320
So one of the things
you may notice

00:12:55.320 --> 00:12:57.920
is that ice sheets grow
much slower than they

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:01.190
melt. It's very easy to
melt an ice sheet quickly.

00:13:01.190 --> 00:13:03.380
And the reason is
because, as you see,

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:05.980
as it starts to retreat,
the ice sheet has

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:07.630
depressed the land under it.

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:11.010
And so the ocean can
flow in very quickly

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:15.160
and destroy that ice sheet from
below as well as from above.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:17.470
So ice sheets can
melt very quickly

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:19.880
because they can become
unstable and warm ocean

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:21.360
can flow under them.

00:13:21.360 --> 00:13:22.640
How quickly?

00:13:22.640 --> 00:13:25.940
This is data-- well,
this is the results

00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:33.960
of a study of Tahiti
in the Western Pacific.

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:36.990
And what the scientists
did was they went offshore

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:38.160
and they drilled down.

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:43.260
And they can, with very
precise dating and drilling,

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:47.350
determine the depth below
sea level of the coral

00:13:47.350 --> 00:13:51.360
as it tracked the sea level rise
at the end of the last ice age.

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:55.190
So as the ice sheets are melting
quickly, the seas are rising,

00:13:55.190 --> 00:13:59.300
the coral is keeping up.

00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:00.420
It can do that.

00:14:00.420 --> 00:14:03.650
And they were able to
determine that as the last ice

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:06.350
sheet deglaciated,
sea level was rising

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:10.450
at rates of 40 millimeters per
year, or 12 feet per century.

00:14:10.450 --> 00:14:14.460
So keep that number in your
mind as we move forward here.

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:17.840
Right now, sea level's
rising to three millimeters

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:20.420
per century-- sorry, per year.

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:21.370
Did I say century?

00:14:21.370 --> 00:14:22.490
I meant year.

00:14:22.490 --> 00:14:24.530
Three millimeters per year.

00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:26.550
But how high was sea
level during some

00:14:26.550 --> 00:14:30.500
of these little periods in the
past that were just slightly

00:14:30.500 --> 00:14:31.750
warmer than today?

00:14:31.750 --> 00:14:34.080
This is a question that's
very easy to answer

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:36.610
and also very
difficult to answer.

00:14:36.610 --> 00:14:38.550
It's very easy
because the evidence

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:42.530
for higher sea levels during the
recent past is all around you.

00:14:42.530 --> 00:14:45.820
This is me standing with my
postdoc, Nick [? O'Leary ?].

00:14:45.820 --> 00:14:49.420
This is the modern Ningaloo reef
system in Northwest Australia.

00:14:49.420 --> 00:14:53.440
We are standing on a
stranded fossilized reef that

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:57.110
is probably about 400,000 years
old from a time period that

00:14:57.110 --> 00:15:00.100
was slightly warmer than today.

00:15:00.100 --> 00:15:01.940
This is a reef.

00:15:01.940 --> 00:15:03.520
This is the fossilized coral.

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:06.400
This is my student Mike
Sandstrom from the Cape ranges

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:07.740
of Western Australia.

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:10.330
That's from the last
interglacial warm period,

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:12.170
125,000 years ago.

00:15:12.170 --> 00:15:15.030
It's a few meters above
present day sea level.

00:15:15.030 --> 00:15:17.790
This is from a three
million year old deposit

00:15:17.790 --> 00:15:21.370
in Pliocene, the Pliocene
warm period in Africa.

00:15:21.370 --> 00:15:25.920
No coral, but we have fossil
oysters with fossil barnacles

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:27.610
still on the fossil oysters.

00:15:27.610 --> 00:15:31.650
I mean, ooh, you're
at sea level.

00:15:31.650 --> 00:15:32.740
But why is it difficult?

00:15:32.740 --> 00:15:36.010
We see this evidence for
high sea levels everywhere.

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:37.860
The major reason
it's difficult is

00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:40.910
because the ocean--
unfortunately, the ocean basin

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:43.170
is not like this tub.

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:46.200
And you can't just look at
these as like bathtub rings

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:48.320
from the past.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:53.500
The continents, the crust of
the sea floor, and the land,

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:54.910
they're constantly in motion.

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:57.020
They're being loaded and
unloaded by ice sheets,

00:15:57.020 --> 00:15:57.600
by water.

00:15:57.600 --> 00:15:59.190
It's constantly moving.

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:01.510
So it's quite a
challenging problem.

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:03.900
And there's a fantastic
group here at Harvard

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:06.590
led by Jerry Mitrovica
that's been working on this.

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:08.820
And many clever
scientists around the room

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:13.650
have made huge progress in
unraveling these challenges

00:16:13.650 --> 00:16:15.700
over the last five to 10 years.

00:16:15.700 --> 00:16:18.970
So I'll jump right to
a summary slide, which

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:22.460
is in a paper we published
in Science last year.

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:25.340
And so here's-- and this is
kind of a complicated slide,

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:26.750
but it's really cool too.

00:16:26.750 --> 00:16:28.390
So here's a CO2 scale.

00:16:28.390 --> 00:16:30.120
There's pre-industrial CO2.

00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:32.050
Here's present day CO2.

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:34.840
And here's a sea level scale.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.040
And here's today's ice volume.

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:40.130
One degree warmer than
pre-industrial right now.

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:43.350
Here's 125,000 years ago.

00:16:43.350 --> 00:16:45.970
The CO2 was the same
during that warm period,

00:16:45.970 --> 00:16:49.760
but we were just so
slightly closer to the sun,

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:50.730
it was warmer.

00:16:50.730 --> 00:16:52.250
It was about one degree warmer.

00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:55.740
A smidge because of the
precession of the Earth varied.

00:16:55.740 --> 00:17:00.186
And all these different
studies as to-- the estimate

00:17:00.186 --> 00:17:01.560
of all these
different studies is

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:04.710
that sea level is six to nine
meters higher than today.

00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:05.460
OK?

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:10.010
And this is a window of time
that's 10,000 years long.

00:17:10.010 --> 00:17:13.030
400,000 years ago, it
was a little bit warmer,

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:15.170
six to 13 meters best estimate.

00:17:15.170 --> 00:17:17.099
And then in the
Pliocene, it's been

00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:18.890
so long, the continents
have moved so much,

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:20.780
we have a very hard time.

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:21.540
Huge error bars.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:23.240
We don't really know.

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:28.520
But two to three degrees warmer,
higher CO2, 400, same as today.

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:33.120
And I wish I could tell you
more exactly what sea level was

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:33.740
at that time.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:35.411
I can't.

00:17:35.411 --> 00:17:35.910
OK.

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:40.160
So you know, this is
6 meters, 20 feet.

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:43.629
Let's take it back to just
four feet, which is completely

00:17:43.629 --> 00:17:45.170
within the realm of
what could happen

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:47.230
by the end of this century.

00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:49.420
I'm perfectly comfortable
with this as a prediction.

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:52.270
And I'm sure there are
others that are as well.

00:17:52.270 --> 00:17:57.810
So four feet above present.

00:17:57.810 --> 00:18:00.620
Five million people live
within four feet of sea level

00:18:00.620 --> 00:18:01.780
in the US today.

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:04.110
It's a huge amount in
Florida, obviously.

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:07.170
And in terms of our national
infrastructure, energy

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:11.420
facilities, ports,
Naval bases, there's

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:17.510
a huge amount of real estate
that is in this zone of risk.

00:18:17.510 --> 00:18:19.920
Obviously, sea level
rise is not just

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:23.270
a problem of the United States.

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:25.250
It's a global problem.

00:18:25.250 --> 00:18:28.910
And we may be hearing more about
the Marshall Islands later too.

00:18:28.910 --> 00:18:31.580
Does anyone recognize
this capital city?

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:35.035
It's Mali.

00:18:35.035 --> 00:18:36.410
It's the capital
of the Maldives.

00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:38.570
And so you have
over 300,000 people

00:18:38.570 --> 00:18:40.870
living on an island that's
a meter and a half above sea

00:18:40.870 --> 00:18:41.670
level.

00:18:41.670 --> 00:18:44.080
And this is just one of
like thousands and thousands

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:46.930
of inhabited islands
around the world.

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:50.500
And when you hear the
expression climate refugees,

00:18:50.500 --> 00:18:52.610
this is what-- these
are people just like us

00:18:52.610 --> 00:18:54.040
that you're hearing about.

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:54.780
OK?

00:18:54.780 --> 00:18:57.650
So I'm going to basically leave
two more possibly depressing

00:18:57.650 --> 00:19:01.560
thoughts about sea level rise.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:03.650
And that is, first of all,
I think a lot of people

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:06.120
have this vague idea they'll
be able to deal with it,

00:19:06.120 --> 00:19:08.870
like keep it back.

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:12.440
I don't believe that's
very realistic, just based

00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:17.380
on my observations of
various places I love.

00:19:17.380 --> 00:19:19.610
And the other thing that's
really important, I think,

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:23.860
for people to come to grips
with and tell themselves

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:26.510
is that sea level rise is
irreversible on the time

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:28.426
scale of centuries.

00:19:28.426 --> 00:19:31.990
You could probably cool
the Earth's atmosphere

00:19:31.990 --> 00:19:34.390
easier than you can
regrow an ice sheet.

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:37.270
So every year, the
increment of water

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:39.950
that's going in from the
melting of polar ice sheets

00:19:39.950 --> 00:19:42.270
and the thermal expansion
of sea water, that's

00:19:42.270 --> 00:19:45.030
an increment of sea
level rise that there,

00:19:45.030 --> 00:19:47.550
and that we're going to have
to deal with for centuries

00:19:47.550 --> 00:19:48.690
to come.

00:19:48.690 --> 00:19:52.350
So to wrap that up,
what I know for sure,

00:19:52.350 --> 00:19:55.020
climate is changing
naturally all the time.

00:19:55.020 --> 00:19:57.810
Small variations,
very small variations

00:19:57.810 --> 00:20:01.460
in incoming solar radiation,
albedo, reflectivity,

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:03.940
and greenhouse
gas concentrations

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:09.010
can lead to large and
sometimes rapid changes.

00:20:09.010 --> 00:20:11.010
The activities of
seven billion people

00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:15.260
are capable of causing
effects of this magnitude.

00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:18.270
And here is the CO2,
carbon dioxide, record

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:20.050
of the last 10,000 years.

00:20:20.050 --> 00:20:22.410
The Holocene, the
warm window of time

00:20:22.410 --> 00:20:29.110
within which human culture,
agriculture flourished.

00:20:29.110 --> 00:20:31.850
It was about 270
parts per million.

00:20:31.850 --> 00:20:34.950
A subtle rise starts
about 5,000 years ago.

00:20:34.950 --> 00:20:37.910
Many scientists believe this
is due to early agricultural

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:39.400
and deforestation.

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:41.770
And then here, this
interval right here,

00:20:41.770 --> 00:20:44.520
blown up right here, here's
the 18th century, the beginning

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:46.150
of the Industrial Revolution.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:49.110
And this rise is
the addition of CO2

00:20:49.110 --> 00:20:53.170
to the atmosphere from the
combustion of fossil fuels.

00:20:53.170 --> 00:20:54.960
And obviously, this
is out of date.

00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:59.180
We're already over 400 PPM.

00:20:59.180 --> 00:21:01.350
I have another video here.

00:21:01.350 --> 00:21:03.010
There it is.

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:08.980
So this is what that CO2 has
done in a very nice visual.

00:21:08.980 --> 00:21:11.520
We humans have cranked the knob.

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:13.580
They've taken the
CO2 dial and they've

00:21:13.580 --> 00:21:16.040
turned it hard to
the right, very hard.

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:19.890
This is a surface
temperature anomaly

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:23.230
map based on instrumental
data from around the world.

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:30.616
Want to see that one again?

00:21:30.616 --> 00:21:31.568
- Yeah.

00:21:31.568 --> 00:21:34.430
- Yeah?

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:35.820
It's cool.

00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:38.760
So what you're
looking at is the mean

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.460
is defined as 1951 to 1980.

00:21:41.460 --> 00:21:44.520
And so what you're looking
at is every surface anomaly

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.820
relative to that mean.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:48.955
So the beginning is generally
lower than the mean.

00:21:48.955 --> 00:21:52.270
And as you see, when
you get towards the end,

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:54.765
you're generally
hotter than the mean.

00:22:02.460 --> 00:22:07.170
In partnership with that
warming atmosphere, heat

00:22:07.170 --> 00:22:09.630
penetrating the ice sheets,
heat penetrating the ocean,

00:22:09.630 --> 00:22:11.830
causing thermal
expansion of the oceans

00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:14.510
and melting of the ice sheets,
sea level has been rising.

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:16.680
These are various
different studies

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:19.310
based on different techniques,
including tide gauges.

00:22:19.310 --> 00:22:23.231
And they're in more disagreement
the further back in time

00:22:23.231 --> 00:22:23.730
you go.

00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:27.340
But I think what everybody
is in agreement about is

00:22:27.340 --> 00:22:31.000
that sea level is rising and
the rate is accelerating.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.460
This is from a post-doc at
Harvard, Carling [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:40.660
And just to take this
time window, 1900 to 2000,

00:22:40.660 --> 00:22:45.370
and put it on a time scale of
the last 2,000 years-- right?

00:22:45.370 --> 00:22:46.800
It's all about
perspective, right?

00:22:46.800 --> 00:22:48.924
Here's that same curve.

00:22:48.924 --> 00:22:50.090
You would put it right here.

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:53.390
So natural variability,
the rise in sea

00:22:53.390 --> 00:22:56.110
level due to two
human-induced global warming.

00:22:56.110 --> 00:22:58.920
So what is the-- I'll
just wrap up here.

00:22:58.920 --> 00:22:59.600
One more slide.

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:01.490
What is the
atmospheric CO2 and sea

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:04.060
level likely to do over
the coming century?

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:06.210
And of course, it's not
just the next 100 years.

00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:09.490
It's many hundreds of
years into the future.

00:23:09.490 --> 00:23:11.270
This is not a
scientific question

00:23:11.270 --> 00:23:14.000
that scientists can answer.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.620
This is a question that's going
to be completely dependent

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:20.550
on the individual and
collective actions of citizens

00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:22.460
and their governments.

00:23:22.460 --> 00:23:24.480
But I will say that
if you look at this,

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:27.730
here is our current
CO2 emission rates.

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:29.800
And what this is
showing is these

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:33.810
are the paths that, as a planet,
we have to choose to be on.

00:23:33.810 --> 00:23:36.380
Can we turn around
global CO2 emission rates

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:38.930
quickly or is it
going to take longer?

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:41.400
And the point to make here
is even if you turned it

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:44.340
around today, you're
still putting CO2

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:45.930
into the atmosphere.

00:23:45.930 --> 00:23:48.410
Much of it's going into
the ocean, but most of it

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:49.410
stays in the atmosphere.

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:52.140
And it will stay there
for hundreds of years.

00:23:52.140 --> 00:23:54.090
So even if you turned
it around today,

00:23:54.090 --> 00:23:56.870
you're committing
yourself to CO2 levels up

00:23:56.870 --> 00:23:58.740
around 500 parts per million.

00:23:58.740 --> 00:24:01.500
Every decade you put it
off, you commit yourself

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:04.050
to higher and higher sea
levels down the road.

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:10.810
So as someone who knows
what these changes in CO2

00:24:10.810 --> 00:24:17.081
have done in the past, this
would be of great concern.

00:24:17.081 --> 00:24:17.580
OK.

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:19.730
So I'll just thank
you for listening.

