you can see there's a
proper ocean up there.

00:25:24.190 --> 00:25:27.400
You can twist this map
round because it is usual

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:28.900
when you're talking
about the Arctic

00:25:28.900 --> 00:25:31.660
to put the country you're
talking in at the bottom.

00:25:31.660 --> 00:25:32.850
Lots of countries here.

00:25:32.850 --> 00:25:35.560
Lots of countries vying
for owning the Arctic.

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:38.210
This picture-- anyone
know this picture?

00:25:38.210 --> 00:25:40.210
This is the Russians
putting their flag

00:25:40.210 --> 00:25:45.240
at the North Pole, three miles
down under the ocean, in 2007,

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:46.284
saying it's theirs.

00:25:46.284 --> 00:25:47.700
We're not going
to go there today,

00:25:47.700 --> 00:25:50.887
but there's interesting
debates about that.

00:25:50.887 --> 00:25:53.220
Give you an idea of scale,
this is relative to something

00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:54.600
I hope you recognize.

00:25:54.600 --> 00:25:56.050
It's bigger than the US.

00:25:56.050 --> 00:25:59.180
If you want some numbers,
here's some numbers on it.

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:02.510
It's the smallest of the
world's five major oceans.

00:26:02.510 --> 00:26:04.590
But it's famous in
many, many ways,

00:26:04.590 --> 00:26:07.550
even before the changes of
recent days, for frozen ships,

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:12.380
for passageways, for the hunt
for the North Pole, et cetera.

00:26:12.380 --> 00:26:16.410
Perhaps of the most poignant
is the Northwest Passage,

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:18.850
which is this route between
the Atlantic Ocean, which

00:26:18.850 --> 00:26:20.080
is down here, and the Arctic.

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:21.940
The search for the
Northwest Passage.

00:26:21.940 --> 00:26:22.960
And let's start there.

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:25.810
Let's start with some
recent Arctic ships.

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:29.877
Can anyone tell me what this is?

00:26:29.877 --> 00:26:33.012
This is the wreck
of the HMS Terror.

00:26:33.012 --> 00:26:37.400
This was a ship which set
sail from England in 1850,

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:40.780
1845, looking for the
Northwest Passage.

00:26:40.780 --> 00:26:43.820
The Franklin Expedition, the
lost Franklin Expedition.

00:26:43.820 --> 00:26:46.080
It's not a happy story.

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:48.720
They overwintered three
years in the archipelago

00:26:48.720 --> 00:26:50.470
trying to find a way through.

00:26:50.470 --> 00:26:53.600
After more than one and a
half years struck in the ice,

00:26:53.600 --> 00:26:56.180
they left the ship trying to
walk South and none of them

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:57.266
survived.

00:26:57.266 --> 00:26:59.390
And since then, we've been
looking for those ships.

00:26:59.390 --> 00:27:01.750
We found those ships
in the last year.

00:27:01.750 --> 00:27:03.560
I say we-- this is Parks Canada.

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:06.510
The Canadians put a lot
of effort into doing this.

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.010
This is the ship
on happier days.

00:27:09.010 --> 00:27:13.010
Some years before this, 1836,
getting stuck in the sea ice

00:27:13.010 --> 00:27:15.910
was an occupational
hazard of being an Arctic

00:27:15.910 --> 00:27:18.580
explorer in those days.

00:27:18.580 --> 00:27:20.470
So another ship in
the news this summer.

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:23.170
Anyone know this one?

00:27:23.170 --> 00:27:26.280
This is the Crystal Serenity,
a luxury cruise liner,

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:28.930
1,000 passengers, 700
crew, which had just

00:27:28.930 --> 00:27:32.300
gone through the same fabled
Northwest Passage in three

00:27:32.300 --> 00:27:34.840
weeks, stopping
in villages which

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:36.950
have a population
less than a third

00:27:36.950 --> 00:27:39.800
of the number of
people on the ship.

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:41.990
Contrast these, the
Franklin's Expedition.

00:27:41.990 --> 00:27:42.670
Here they are.

00:27:42.670 --> 00:27:43.947
This is as far as they got.

00:27:43.947 --> 00:27:46.030
This is where, basically,
the whole crew perished.

00:27:46.030 --> 00:27:47.560
Nobody came home.

00:27:47.560 --> 00:27:50.130
And the Crystal
Serenity, which has

00:27:50.130 --> 00:27:52.370
gone through in a nice
planned trip for three weeks,

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:53.860
come out in New York.

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:55.000
What's the difference?

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:57.030
The difference
between this is ice.

00:27:57.030 --> 00:27:58.960
Let's talk about ice.

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:02.690
So if I take sea
water and freeze it,

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:04.190
I start to get very
little crystals.

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:06.010
They float up to the
surface of the ocean.

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:09.620
They form a kind
of an oily layer

00:28:09.620 --> 00:28:12.590
on the top of the ocean, which
gradually pushes together

00:28:12.590 --> 00:28:13.931
to form a sheet of ice.

00:28:13.931 --> 00:28:14.430
OK.

00:28:14.430 --> 00:28:15.927
This has some resilience.

00:28:15.927 --> 00:28:17.510
I wouldn't walk on
this at this stage,

00:28:17.510 --> 00:28:19.676
but it will push together
and you can see the edges.

00:28:19.676 --> 00:28:22.960
You can see here the
striations of the layers

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:24.960
push against each other.

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:27.090
Let it go a bit further
and these layers

00:28:27.090 --> 00:28:28.400
form into more sheets.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:30.150
If you're a penguin,
you can walk on this.

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:33.530
No, there are no
penguins in the Arctic.

00:28:33.530 --> 00:28:37.080
As these sheets come together,
we call this pancake ice.

00:28:37.080 --> 00:28:40.670
People at sea will think
of a lot of things.

00:28:40.670 --> 00:28:44.450
And they get thicker and come
together over a period a few

00:28:44.450 --> 00:28:46.520
more days to make
into ice floes.

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:49.080
Ice floes can be several yards
to a mile to several miles

00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:49.580
across.

00:28:49.580 --> 00:28:51.621
I don't know how you got
here, but this gives you

00:28:51.621 --> 00:28:52.820
an idea of scale.

00:28:52.820 --> 00:28:56.430
This is the first time that
I would walk on this stuff.

00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:59.090
This is about one
to two meters thick.

00:28:59.090 --> 00:29:00.230
So here to here thick.

00:29:00.230 --> 00:29:02.837
This is first year ice,
will form over season.

00:29:02.837 --> 00:29:04.420
Here's a ship plowing
through the ice.

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:06.440
As it goes through, it
pushes the ice up on edge

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:10.871
so you can see how thick the
ice is from here to here.

00:29:10.871 --> 00:29:13.120
This is not how we get the
thickest ice in the Arctic.

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:15.520
If you just let it grow
over more than one year,

00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:19.030
it would grow to three
meters, not quite reach that.

00:29:19.030 --> 00:29:20.095
Nine feet tall.

00:29:20.095 --> 00:29:22.470
But what makes it really thick
is as those pieces of ice,

00:29:22.470 --> 00:29:25.010
those floes of ice push
together, they ridge,

00:29:25.010 --> 00:29:26.910
just like a mountain
range will ridge.

00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:30.180
And this is what makes our
thickest pieces of ice.

00:29:30.180 --> 00:29:34.030
I've put here a picture from
one of the pretty buildings

00:29:34.030 --> 00:29:35.590
from my university.

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:37.080
90 feet tall is this tower.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:39.550
And that is a not atypical
height for a ridge

00:29:39.550 --> 00:29:41.570
that you'd get in the Arctic.

00:29:41.570 --> 00:29:44.340
Just like an iceberg, there's
more below than above.

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:47.720
So if we have this chap
standing here beside the ice,

00:29:47.720 --> 00:29:50.790
and we measure how far
above the water he would be

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:52.380
and how far below
the keel, you're

00:29:52.380 --> 00:29:54.970
looking about an ice keel about
the height of that building.

00:29:54.970 --> 00:29:57.370
So these are common
sizes of thicknesses

00:29:57.370 --> 00:29:59.890
of ice in the Arctic.

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:01.730
Now, while this is
pushing together here,

00:30:01.730 --> 00:30:03.637
it's coming apart
somewhere else.

00:30:03.637 --> 00:30:05.220
And this gives us
what is called leads

00:30:05.220 --> 00:30:08.330
in the ice, cracks in the ice
which can appear overnight.

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:09.190
Very, very quickly.

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:11.770
Sometimes in
inconvenient places.

00:30:11.770 --> 00:30:14.324
This is a current hazard
of Arctic exploration,

00:30:14.324 --> 00:30:16.240
as you might get a lead
come through your camp

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:20.330
in the middle of the night,
with interesting consequences.

00:30:20.330 --> 00:30:22.500
Didn't fall in, we
don't really mind.

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:25.437
I prefer to work off
ships for that reason.

00:30:25.437 --> 00:30:26.770
And you can see some ships here.

00:30:26.770 --> 00:30:29.540
Here the ship is giving
the scale of the ice floes.

00:30:29.540 --> 00:30:32.544
As the summer carries
on, the sun melts,

00:30:32.544 --> 00:30:34.210
the snow on the top
of the ice gives you

00:30:34.210 --> 00:30:36.530
melt ponds in the top of the
ice, which will eventually

00:30:36.530 --> 00:30:39.060
decay the ice away.

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:41.560
It is a habitat
for life, is ice.

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:43.730
We have our
charismatic megafauna.

00:30:43.730 --> 00:30:46.810
And we have our, perhaps, not
so charismatic tiny fauna.

00:30:46.810 --> 00:30:50.140
This little brown striations
you see here, that's not mud

00:30:50.140 --> 00:30:51.810
and that's not
paint off the ship.

00:30:51.810 --> 00:30:55.800
That is actually little
microbial community plankton

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:57.659
which are growing in
the channels of ice.

00:30:57.659 --> 00:30:58.700
You can do this yourself.

00:30:58.700 --> 00:31:01.690
Go home, take some salty
water, chuck it in the freezer.

00:31:01.690 --> 00:31:04.076
And tomorrow morning, put
drops of food coloring in it

00:31:04.076 --> 00:31:05.450
and you can see
the channels that

00:31:05.450 --> 00:31:09.560
go through the sea ice
which are channels for life.

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:11.330
It's also home for people.

00:31:11.330 --> 00:31:13.040
The Inuit have
made their history

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:15.500
in the Arctic for 10,000 years.

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:17.112
And to them, ice
is not a hindrance.

00:31:17.112 --> 00:31:18.570
Ice is their way
of getting around.

00:31:18.570 --> 00:31:21.370
Ice is their highway.

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:23.140
So where are we today?

00:31:23.140 --> 00:31:25.200
This is almost
today's sea ice there.

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:27.320
This is a satellite image.

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:28.880
Greenland's here.

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:30.960
The colors give you
the ice concentration.

00:31:30.960 --> 00:31:32.590
These dark areas are water.

00:31:32.590 --> 00:31:34.510
You can see the sea
ice now building up

00:31:34.510 --> 00:31:37.700
from it's expanding as
the winter has started

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:40.070
in the North, expanding
back out to the coasts

00:31:40.070 --> 00:31:43.530
and down into the
lower latitudes.

00:31:43.530 --> 00:31:45.260
That's a snapshot of today.

00:31:45.260 --> 00:31:47.610
It's a large seasonal
cycle in the sea ice.

00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:49.540
This again, satellite data.

00:31:49.540 --> 00:31:51.430
We're over here,
again, now showing

00:31:51.430 --> 00:31:55.180
the maximum extent in winter and
the minimum extent in summer.

00:31:55.180 --> 00:31:57.390
Occur March and
September respectively.

00:31:57.390 --> 00:31:59.780
Large seasonal
change, of course,

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:01.926
because the sun comes
up and melts the ice.

00:32:01.926 --> 00:32:04.090
Well, how does this year
compare with the past?

00:32:04.090 --> 00:32:06.960
We have this satellite
data back to 1979.

00:32:06.960 --> 00:32:08.840
And I pulled out
the years which have

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:13.140
the maximums in the seasons and
the minimums in the seasons.

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:14.800
And to make it a
bit easier to see,

00:32:14.800 --> 00:32:17.120
I'm going to change it
now to sea ice extent.

00:32:17.120 --> 00:32:19.170
And this pink line
in both of these maps

00:32:19.170 --> 00:32:23.030
shows the monthly median
edge from '81 to 2010.

00:32:23.030 --> 00:32:25.820
So what we thought was standard
for most of our satellite

00:32:25.820 --> 00:32:27.010
record.

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:30.340
So in the winters, you know,
we're kind of close to that.

00:32:30.340 --> 00:32:31.540
Getting a few changes.

00:32:31.540 --> 00:32:34.230
But the summers, we're seeing
this very dramatic loss

00:32:34.230 --> 00:32:35.930
of sea ice.

00:32:35.930 --> 00:32:37.740
Let's put those on time scales.

00:32:37.740 --> 00:32:40.080
Here we have the whole
time series we have,

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:41.752
and the trend line through that.

00:32:41.752 --> 00:32:42.710
And it's not very much.

00:32:42.710 --> 00:32:44.880
It's a few percent per decade.

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:46.030
This is the winter.

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:49.470
But in the summer, we're getting
a very much greater change,

00:32:49.470 --> 00:32:51.450
13% per decade.

00:32:51.450 --> 00:32:51.950
OK.

00:32:51.950 --> 00:32:54.415
That's we're losing--
13% of the ice per decade

00:32:54.415 --> 00:32:55.540
we're losing in the Arctic.

00:32:58.910 --> 00:33:01.295
To look at where we're
losing it, in the winter,

00:33:01.295 --> 00:33:02.670
we're losing it
around the edges.

00:33:02.670 --> 00:33:04.560
In the summer, we're
losing it in the middle.

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:07.510
We'll come back to these
patterns in a moment.

00:33:07.510 --> 00:33:09.090
So we're losing ice area?

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:10.030
Oh, yeah.

00:33:10.030 --> 00:33:12.030
The area that we've lost
so far is about a third

00:33:12.030 --> 00:33:13.190
of the area of the US.

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:15.620
And we've probably
lost about 50%

00:33:15.620 --> 00:33:19.850
of the old summer sea ice
extent, from about the 1980s.

00:33:19.850 --> 00:33:21.350
It's not just that
that we've lost.

00:33:21.350 --> 00:33:23.880
We've also thinned the ice.

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:25.380
So it's harder to
put this together.

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:29.530
We put together from submarines
and satellite images.

00:33:29.530 --> 00:33:31.920
But this gives you an
idea, in the 1980s--

00:33:31.920 --> 00:33:35.250
this is winter and summer-- we
had about three meters of ice.

00:33:35.250 --> 00:33:38.711
And now, in more recent era,
we're down to about half that.

00:33:38.711 --> 00:33:41.210
This satellite picture's showing
you how that's distributed.

00:33:41.210 --> 00:33:43.474
There's lots of statistics
that have to go into this.

00:33:43.474 --> 00:33:44.890
But this is confirmed
by everybody

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:46.764
who goes up there, the
people who live there,

00:33:46.764 --> 00:33:48.640
who talk about--
saying we no longer get

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:50.740
the strong, thick
ice we used to have.

00:33:50.740 --> 00:33:54.700
We only have feeble,
weak, young ice.

00:33:54.700 --> 00:33:59.180
So you can say sea ice is thin
from very roughly about 50%.

00:33:59.180 --> 00:34:02.020
Put that together, we've
lost extent, we've thinned.

00:34:02.020 --> 00:34:03.580
We end up with a loss of volume.

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:06.038
This is our best estimate to
try and put that all together,

00:34:06.038 --> 00:34:11.130
which is a model, and which
says we have lost basically 30%.

00:34:11.130 --> 00:34:14.350
No, we've not lost 30%,
we only have 30% left

00:34:14.350 --> 00:34:16.460
of the summer ice
that used to have.

00:34:16.460 --> 00:34:16.960
OK?

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:18.340
Some people will say
this is a quarter,

00:34:18.340 --> 00:34:19.631
but it's around that magnitude.

00:34:19.631 --> 00:34:21.980
So there's a huge change
we've seen in the Arctic

00:34:21.980 --> 00:34:23.969
in the last decades.

00:34:23.969 --> 00:34:26.559
How did we get here?

00:34:26.559 --> 00:34:27.214
Polar bear.

00:34:27.214 --> 00:34:28.880
We're always going
to have a polar bear.

00:34:28.880 --> 00:34:31.570
How did he get there either?

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:33.350
So we got there in many ways.

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:36.582
Things that we understand
and things that we don't.

00:34:36.582 --> 00:34:40.370
We understand now how
well the ice moves.

00:34:40.370 --> 00:34:45.100
So if we put a pole in
the ice at the North Pole,

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:48.139
the floe drifts around
and the ice moves with it.

00:34:48.139 --> 00:34:49.790
To be more useful
in that, we can

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:52.870
put in a set of
instruments which

00:34:52.870 --> 00:34:54.739
will tell you their position.

00:34:54.739 --> 00:34:58.320
So dates rolling
in the corner here.

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:00.940
White is the satellite
sea ice extent

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:02.704
going from the
summer to the winter

00:35:02.704 --> 00:35:03.870
to the summer to the winter.

00:35:03.870 --> 00:35:05.810
And the little red
dots are buoys that

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:08.110
have been put on the ice
and register their position.

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:10.500
You see they go around in a
kind of circle around here.

00:35:10.500 --> 00:35:12.990
Some of them run down the
edge of Greenland like this.

00:35:12.990 --> 00:35:14.406
This is how the
sea ice is moving.

00:35:14.406 --> 00:35:16.697
They're just sat on the sea ice.

00:35:16.697 --> 00:35:18.530
They jiggle around
together because the wind

00:35:18.530 --> 00:35:19.750
is forcing them.

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:22.010
And we can see this pattern
of a circulation there,

00:35:22.010 --> 00:35:25.290
and then ice coming around here
and coming out down this way.

00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:29.380
And as we come to the 2000s,
we see the summer extent

00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:31.280
getting less every year.

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:33.620
And we can see this melting
back to this incredible ice

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:36.690
melt in 2007, which really was
something that nobody expected

00:35:36.690 --> 00:35:39.270
or saw coming.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:42.940
So from that data, we can
go on and say, well, we

00:35:42.940 --> 00:35:44.400
can see how this is moving.

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:46.590
We can tell how old the ice is.

00:35:46.590 --> 00:35:49.510
And this is a similar movie
where the colors are now

00:35:49.510 --> 00:35:51.190
the age of the ice.

00:35:51.190 --> 00:35:53.130
So white is now
greater than 10 years,

00:35:53.130 --> 00:35:56.170
and these bluer colors are more
recent, younger ice than that.

00:35:56.170 --> 00:35:58.130
It's the same buoys
as you saw before.

00:35:58.130 --> 00:36:01.400
We're seeing here in the
1980s, most of the Arctic

00:36:01.400 --> 00:36:04.710
was covered by old ice.

00:36:04.710 --> 00:36:06.886
But changes in the
wind have changed that.

00:36:06.886 --> 00:36:08.260
We've taken all
this area of ice,

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:10.070
then managed to flush
it out down here

00:36:10.070 --> 00:36:11.820
through to the Atlantic Ocean.

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:15.030
And over this time period,
we're losing the older ice

00:36:15.030 --> 00:36:16.840
in the Arctic and
coming back to just

00:36:16.840 --> 00:36:20.190
having a very much younger,
newer ice in the Arctic Ocean.

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:23.410
We've flushed the
old stuff all away.

00:36:23.410 --> 00:36:26.044
To see the before and after, if
you like, here is the before.

00:36:26.044 --> 00:36:26.710
Lots of old ice.

00:36:26.710 --> 00:36:30.070
And here is the new with
very little ice left.

00:36:30.070 --> 00:36:32.560
In doing that,
we've flushed away

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:34.570
the old, thick, resilient ice.

00:36:34.570 --> 00:36:37.912
It now moves faster
and it's thinner.

00:36:37.912 --> 00:36:39.370
The other thing
that goes with that

00:36:39.370 --> 00:36:41.840
is that it can also melt easier.

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.160
If we look at how
things have changed,

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:45.940
is it just due to this motion?

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:47.080
No, it's not.

00:36:47.080 --> 00:36:54.070
This is a movie of 2000, again
looking at ice and clouds now.

00:36:57.780 --> 00:36:59.870
So here's Greenland again.

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:03.280
And you see here the coast of
Alaska around these points.

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:05.760
The big things that
swell past are clouds.

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:07.260
But mostly, what
you see underneath,

00:37:07.260 --> 00:37:08.700
this is the ice moving.

00:37:08.700 --> 00:37:10.150
Sometimes the wind blows.

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:11.500
You'll see black open up here.

00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:15.150
That's open water opening up
along the coast you see here.

00:37:15.150 --> 00:37:16.667
You see-- if you
watch this bit, you

00:37:16.667 --> 00:37:18.250
can kind of sense
the motion, which is

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:19.710
the same motion we saw before.

00:37:19.710 --> 00:37:21.270
You see these
massive cracks coming

00:37:21.270 --> 00:37:22.380
across the whole of the Arctic.

00:37:22.380 --> 00:37:24.046
Those are the leads
that we talked about

00:37:24.046 --> 00:37:26.920
as the ice pulls apart
driven by winds and currents.

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:29.510
In summer here, the ice starts
to pull back from the coast.

00:37:29.510 --> 00:37:32.477
And you can see here the retreat
of the edge, which is faster

00:37:32.477 --> 00:37:33.560
than the speed of the ice.

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:35.351
Basically, as we watch
those through August

00:37:35.351 --> 00:37:39.760
and through September, that
ice just entirely melts away.

00:37:43.160 --> 00:37:44.230
OK.

00:37:44.230 --> 00:37:47.880
So what causes it to melt?

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:50.530
The main thing is this idea
of an ice albedo feedback.

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:53.390
This is the reflectivity that
was talked about a second ago.

00:37:53.390 --> 00:37:57.520
Quite simply, the ice is
shiny and the water is not.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:00.300
So if sunlight beats on the
ice, it reflects that heat back

00:38:00.300 --> 00:38:00.840
to space.

00:38:00.840 --> 00:38:03.200
If it beats on open water,
that heat is absorbed

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:04.790
and we get a feedback.

00:38:04.790 --> 00:38:08.370
Let's say we start
with more ocean water.

00:38:08.370 --> 00:38:10.410
That water can absorb more heat.

00:38:10.410 --> 00:38:13.270
That means it will
get warmer, which

00:38:13.270 --> 00:38:15.560
means it will melt
some more ice, which

00:38:15.560 --> 00:38:17.640
means we have more open
water, which means we

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:19.210
go round and round this circle.

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:20.770
It's a vicious circle.

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:23.190
A vicious circle of
demise of sea ice.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:27.870
The technical physical term for
that is a positive feedback.

00:38:27.870 --> 00:38:30.610
And so once we can set
this off, the only thing

00:38:30.610 --> 00:38:33.180
that's going to stop this
is by turning off the light.

00:38:33.180 --> 00:38:36.060
Winter coming is the only thing
that will stop this feedback.

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:37.350
But we have to set this off.

00:38:37.350 --> 00:38:39.472
And to set this
off, what can we do?

00:38:39.472 --> 00:38:40.930
We can blow the
wind off the coast.

00:38:40.930 --> 00:38:42.971
But there's a further role
which is bringing heat

00:38:42.971 --> 00:38:45.200
into the Arctic, and
that is the oceans.

00:38:45.200 --> 00:38:47.900
This is now a map of the
bathymetry of the Arctic Ocean.

00:38:47.900 --> 00:38:50.880
Deep bits of blue about the
size of our local volcano

00:38:50.880 --> 00:38:52.380
in Seattle.

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:54.992
The shallow red bits
are more shallow.

00:38:54.992 --> 00:38:56.450
And there's other
things there that

00:38:56.450 --> 00:38:57.970
give you some idea of scales.

00:38:57.970 --> 00:38:59.970
We have an entrance here
to the Atlantic Ocean,

00:38:59.970 --> 00:39:01.303
an entrance here to the Pacific.

00:39:01.303 --> 00:39:04.870
And waters flow from both of
those oceans into the Arctic.

00:39:04.870 --> 00:39:07.820
Here's the Atlantic water which
comes in, the deep current.

00:39:07.820 --> 00:39:10.080
And it likes to put its
hand on the right hand wall

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:12.330
like a good current should
in the Northern hemisphere,

00:39:12.330 --> 00:39:13.650
because the Earth is spinning.

00:39:13.650 --> 00:39:16.650
And it goes around
following slopes and ridges.

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:21.100
It goes around very slowly,
a few centimeters per second.

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:22.890
So it'll take eight
hours to go one mile.

00:39:22.890 --> 00:39:24.512
So if we send some
water in here,

00:39:24.512 --> 00:39:26.470
depending whether it
takes the short route back

00:39:26.470 --> 00:39:29.570
through here or the longer
loops back through here,

00:39:29.570 --> 00:39:33.610
it can take 10, 20, or 30
years to get back out again.

00:39:33.610 --> 00:39:35.550
So we send a heat
signal into the Arctic,

00:39:35.550 --> 00:39:38.870
that the time it's going to
go around and then come back.

00:39:38.870 --> 00:39:41.249
On the other side, the water
comes from the Pacific.

00:39:41.249 --> 00:39:42.790
That's higher up in
the water column.

00:39:42.790 --> 00:39:43.950
It's also a lot fresher.

00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:47.030
It tends to stay with
the top of the ocean.

00:39:47.030 --> 00:39:49.200
And it's more driven by
the ice and by the winds.

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:51.060
It moves a lot faster.

00:39:51.060 --> 00:39:54.830
It actually covers about
half of the Arctic Ocean

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:57.800
here, then comes out through
the Canadian archipelago.

00:39:57.800 --> 00:40:01.060
So it will only take about
10 years to cross the Arctic.

00:40:01.060 --> 00:40:02.990
What both these currents
have in common is

00:40:02.990 --> 00:40:05.682
they bring in heat
to the Arctic Ocean.

00:40:05.682 --> 00:40:07.390
Here's some pictures
off the Fram Strait,

00:40:07.390 --> 00:40:11.200
seeing the heat from the ocean
coming up and melting the ice.

00:40:11.200 --> 00:40:13.170
If we look at that
Atlantic layer, [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:16.110
that we had for that, and
we look at the ice edge,

00:40:16.110 --> 00:40:18.760
we can see here these
tongues of hot water coming

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:21.910
across Greenland
and the Bering Sea

00:40:21.910 --> 00:40:24.330
here, melting back the ice edge.

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:25.712
Very suggestive
from the patterns

00:40:25.712 --> 00:40:27.670
that the oceans are
bringing in the heat, which

00:40:27.670 --> 00:40:29.570
is melting off the ice.

00:40:29.570 --> 00:40:31.489
And I show you
that as a pattern,

00:40:31.489 --> 00:40:32.530
that we can do the maths.

00:40:32.530 --> 00:40:34.730
We've had measurements
in these channels

00:40:34.730 --> 00:40:36.910
at great expense for many years.

00:40:36.910 --> 00:40:39.340
We can see that
over these decades,

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:41.800
the temperature of the
waters have warmed as we

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:43.049
go through the channel there.

00:40:43.049 --> 00:40:45.090
And you can do the maths,
so you can work it out.

00:40:45.090 --> 00:40:47.610
But we're just about right
for the numbers, the amount

00:40:47.610 --> 00:40:50.840
of winter ice that we're
losing in this area, which

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:53.220
is 10% per decade in
this particular area,

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:57.600
is likely caused by an ocean
warming of 0.3% per decade.

00:40:57.600 --> 00:40:59.480
It corresponds to
that map we had

00:40:59.480 --> 00:41:03.210
of where we saw the ice
going away in winter.

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:05.150
We flip over to the
other side of the Arctic,

00:41:05.150 --> 00:41:07.115
the Pacific, here
the water's coming in

00:41:07.115 --> 00:41:08.380
and only warm in the summer.

00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:10.080
But we see the same pattern.

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:12.490
We have here the same,
the tongues of water,

00:41:12.490 --> 00:41:16.220
again driven by the topography,
melt back tongues in the ice.

00:41:16.220 --> 00:41:16.990
And this is now.

00:41:16.990 --> 00:41:18.420
We've got the sun up here.

00:41:18.420 --> 00:41:19.350
We can set this off.

00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:22.420
And now the ice albedo feedback
can take over and melt back

00:41:22.420 --> 00:41:23.189
the ice.

00:41:23.189 --> 00:41:24.730
The other thing that
this water does,

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:26.727
it ends up deeper
in the Arctic Ocean

00:41:26.727 --> 00:41:28.310
and it can add to
the gradual thinning

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:29.520
to the ice that is there.

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:32.697
Yet another nail in the coffin
of the poor Arctic sea ice.

00:41:32.697 --> 00:41:34.780
Again, we've had measurements
here for many years.

00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:36.490
We can see this heat
flow increasing.

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:38.520
And we can do the
maths, and we can say,

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:40.680
this is the effect
of these heat flows.

00:41:40.680 --> 00:41:44.640
We've got warmer waters
coming in from both sides.

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:49.530
So what is our causes of
recent sea ice retreat?

00:41:49.530 --> 00:41:51.760
The increased heat
from the Pacific,

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:53.830
increased heat
from the Atlantic.

00:41:53.830 --> 00:41:55.860
Warmer atmospheres I
haven't talked about,

00:41:55.860 --> 00:41:57.720
but that's coming into this too.

00:41:57.720 --> 00:41:59.500
Added on to a
preconditioning, where

00:41:59.500 --> 00:42:01.950
we have flushed this older
ice out of the Arctic.

00:42:01.950 --> 00:42:03.550
So all of these
things are conspiring

00:42:03.550 --> 00:42:05.641
to give the Arctic
a really bad day.

00:42:05.641 --> 00:42:06.140
Right?

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:08.110
We've all had bad
days like this.

00:42:08.110 --> 00:42:11.080
This is the Arctic's bad day.

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:13.080
Quite how these interplays,
things that we still

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:14.180
have to put together.

00:42:14.180 --> 00:42:16.900
We have so far not
managed to predict

00:42:16.900 --> 00:42:20.640
any of these extreme ice
melt years that we have had.

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:23.830
So what sort of
a hole are we in?

00:42:23.830 --> 00:42:26.630
This guy-- this is how we used
to do Arctic oceanography.

00:42:26.630 --> 00:42:29.680
This is one of our technicians
who has chiseled his way down

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:31.140
through a bit of sea ice.

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:32.690
OK, this is a good
bit of sea ice.

00:42:32.690 --> 00:42:35.790
Chiseling down so he can
get to the ocean below.

00:42:35.790 --> 00:42:36.320
OK?

00:42:36.320 --> 00:42:39.420
Digging himself a hole.

00:42:39.420 --> 00:42:44.180
The ice albedo feedback is kind
of a killer in all of this.

00:42:44.180 --> 00:42:46.200
It comes with the idea
of polar amplification.

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:48.419
We saw that in an earlier
video, though you may not

00:42:48.419 --> 00:42:49.460
have been looking for it.

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:51.900
The poles are going to warm
first, especially the Arctic,

00:42:51.900 --> 00:42:53.760
because we are
losing the albedo.

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:55.620
We're losing the
shininess of the Earth,

00:42:55.620 --> 00:42:57.610
and we're allowing
all that energy

00:42:57.610 --> 00:43:00.150
to absorb into the ocean.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:02.880
Quite how that is going to play
out as we push those Arctic

00:43:02.880 --> 00:43:05.250
waters into the
rest of the world,

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:07.280
we haven't quite worked out.

00:43:07.280 --> 00:43:10.370
That's more Lynne's
field than mine.

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:12.490
What also comes with
this is a change

00:43:12.490 --> 00:43:15.040
in the atmospheric circulation.

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:17.450
There is a cap of
cold air which sits

00:43:17.450 --> 00:43:21.450
over the Arctic which basically
can get extra wobbles on it.

00:43:21.450 --> 00:43:23.820
And those wobbles are thought
to be driven by changes

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:24.970
in the sea ice extent.

00:43:24.970 --> 00:43:26.985
And that gives us the
cold air outbreaks

00:43:26.985 --> 00:43:29.860
and the dumping of snow onto
the East Coast that we've

00:43:29.860 --> 00:43:31.830
seen in recent years.

00:43:31.830 --> 00:43:34.400
This is how the Arctic
extends its fingers down

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:36.610
into mid-latitude weather.

00:43:36.610 --> 00:43:39.040
There is also the
impact in the Arctic

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:42.300
of where the warming
that we're having,

00:43:42.300 --> 00:43:45.112
permafrost thawing, loss of
ice protection from erosion.

00:43:45.112 --> 00:43:46.820
If the ice pulls back
earlier, the storms

00:43:46.820 --> 00:43:48.190
can affect things more.

00:43:48.190 --> 00:43:51.150
And we have whole villages
falling into the sea.

00:43:51.150 --> 00:43:53.850
Loss of infrastructure
in terms of roads,

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:56.300
buildings that are
built on permafrost.

00:43:56.300 --> 00:43:58.870
Also within the permafrost,
we have a large store

00:43:58.870 --> 00:44:00.310
of methane hydrates.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:03.690
These are frozen
methane under the sea.

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:05.250
Currently stable,
but as we warm,

00:44:05.250 --> 00:44:09.290
we could release that with
potentially huge consequences.

00:44:09.290 --> 00:44:11.960
We don't quite know how that
one will play out either.

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:15.780
We also have with
this the opportunities

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:18.600
which are coming from this--
exploitation of resources

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:21.380
and Arctic shipping,
which can now talk

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:23.000
about going across the pole.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.667
And in all of this too,
we think about the peoples

00:44:25.667 --> 00:44:26.500
and the governments.

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:28.230
There are people
who live up there,

00:44:28.230 --> 00:44:29.650
who this is their way of life.

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:32.150
And there are the governments
of the world who are clamoring

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:34.416
to own that piece of the ocean.

00:44:34.416 --> 00:44:36.540
So what have we seen in
our trip around the Arctic?

00:44:36.540 --> 00:44:39.440
We've changed the seasonal
ice extent, how it changes.

00:44:39.440 --> 00:44:40.555
How we've thinned the ice.

00:44:40.555 --> 00:44:42.820
If you take just that one
number, take away this.

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:45.690
We're only left
with 30% of the ice

00:44:45.690 --> 00:44:49.260
that we used to have in the
summer just a few decades ago.

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:52.710
We've looked at why that
things might be causing that.

00:44:52.710 --> 00:44:56.200
And we've looked at the possible
implications of all of this.

00:44:56.200 --> 00:44:59.160
It's a field which, because
of the ramifications,

00:44:59.160 --> 00:45:02.080
these broad ramifications, and
the way the thing interacts,

00:45:02.080 --> 00:45:04.990
we really need not just an
interdisciplinary, but also

00:45:04.990 --> 00:45:06.880
a cross-cultural
approach to have

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:09.170
a responsible and coherent
way of going forward

00:45:09.170 --> 00:45:11.150
into the future.

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:11.990
Thank you.

00:45:11.990 --> 00:45:15.215
[APPLAUSE]

