00:45:56.430 --> 00:45:58.130
And I'm going to
talk a bit about how

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:01.600
we get from oceans
to drought, or what

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:04.980
we can learn about the
water cycle of the planet

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:07.870
from what we measure
in the ocean.

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:12.320
And I actually have a very
brief set of definitions,

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:15.416
because we have-- actually,
speaking from a place of-- I'm

00:46:15.416 --> 00:46:17.800
going to show a lot of results
from the Intergovernmental

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:20.220
Panel on Climate Change, IPCC.

00:46:20.220 --> 00:46:22.090
I had the great privilege
to be part of it

00:46:22.090 --> 00:46:25.960
the last two reports we put
together the first time.

00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:28.860
It had an oceans
chapter two times ago.

00:46:28.860 --> 00:46:30.650
And we continued
that with this one.

00:46:30.650 --> 00:46:32.108
So I'm going to
show a lot of stuff

00:46:32.108 --> 00:46:36.220
from a particular slant
in the IPCC of how

00:46:36.220 --> 00:46:37.920
the oceans are
changing and how they

00:46:37.920 --> 00:46:39.332
contribute to climate change.

00:46:39.332 --> 00:46:41.540
But first, you want to know
what we're talking about.

00:46:41.540 --> 00:46:43.390
So there's climate.

00:46:43.390 --> 00:46:44.820
And there's climate variability.

00:46:44.820 --> 00:46:45.800
We have a lot of that.

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:47.550
And there's El Nino.

00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:50.740
Some years are stormy, some
years are not, et cetera.

00:46:50.740 --> 00:46:51.880
That's natural.

00:46:51.880 --> 00:46:54.340
And we have major natural
climate variability

00:46:54.340 --> 00:46:55.610
on the planet.

00:46:55.610 --> 00:46:59.140
And that can be affected
by climate change, which

00:46:59.140 --> 00:47:02.480
is what we drive through
anthropogenic forcing.

00:47:02.480 --> 00:47:05.480
And so we're seeing all
kinds of records now.

00:47:05.480 --> 00:47:08.810
So I just want to get those
