[INAUDIBLE] such

00:47:12.310 --> 00:47:15.010
that we have a framework there.

00:47:15.010 --> 00:47:20.220
These are four major overarching
conclusions from the IPCC.

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:21.580
This is not the oceans part.

00:47:21.580 --> 00:47:23.270
This is the whole thing.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:27.980
Number one, which Susan Solomon
put forward in the 2007 IPCC

00:47:27.980 --> 00:47:29.700
as the head of the
working Group 1,

00:47:29.700 --> 00:47:32.490
warming of the climate
system is unequivocal.

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:35.010
We came home from that
with buttons to wear.

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:37.500
Warming is unequivocal.

00:47:37.500 --> 00:47:39.850
Global warming does
not cause ice ages.

00:47:39.850 --> 00:47:41.690
That was the second
part of that.

00:47:41.690 --> 00:47:45.030
Number two, human influence
on the climate is clear.

00:47:45.030 --> 00:47:48.390
Number three, continued
greenhouse gas emissions

00:47:48.390 --> 00:47:49.900
will cause further warming.

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:52.340
And number four,
limiting climate change

00:47:52.340 --> 00:47:56.110
requires substantial sustained
reductions of emissions.

00:47:56.110 --> 00:47:57.750
So let's look at the Earth.

00:47:57.750 --> 00:47:59.000
Is it warming?

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.290
We've already seen
this in video.

00:48:01.290 --> 00:48:04.950
This is the trend since
1901 up through 2012.

00:48:04.950 --> 00:48:07.040
Where it's white is where
there's not enough data.

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:08.570
Mostly it's warming.

00:48:08.570 --> 00:48:09.530
There it is.

00:48:09.530 --> 00:48:11.120
And it's mostly
warming over land,

00:48:11.120 --> 00:48:13.473
but it's warming over the
sea, and that's important.

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:19.947
This is from this wonderful
NASA website, climate.nasa.gov.

00:48:19.947 --> 00:48:22.530
Go on there if you want to put
something on your Facebook page

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:23.820
there every day from there.

00:48:23.820 --> 00:48:24.980
It's great.

00:48:24.980 --> 00:48:26.690
There is our graph.

00:48:26.690 --> 00:48:29.710
And when you go online,
actually, that red

00:48:29.710 --> 00:48:31.370
dot at the end animates.

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:32.330
Boom, boom, boom.

00:48:32.330 --> 00:48:36.570
It's the hottest ever
measured with direct records

00:48:36.570 --> 00:48:37.700
this past year.

00:48:37.700 --> 00:48:41.130
And this year, 2016, was higher.

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:42.710
So there we are.

00:48:42.710 --> 00:48:44.640
We're getting warmer.

00:48:44.640 --> 00:48:47.580
And they give you a nice number
for how much warmer we are.

00:48:47.580 --> 00:48:50.800
It's almost one degree warmer.

00:48:50.800 --> 00:48:53.270
It's projected to get warmer.

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:55.650
And there's-- the IPCC has
different ways of going about

00:48:55.650 --> 00:48:59.560
that with business as usual, or
some reductions, or whatever.

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:02.200
So you get from
moderate to extreme.

00:49:02.200 --> 00:49:04.910
The one on the left is--
the right, your right,

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:06.380
is obviously more extreme.

00:49:06.380 --> 00:49:08.930
But that's where we're going
if you just burn it all.

00:49:08.930 --> 00:49:11.960
And you see the
polar amplification

00:49:11.960 --> 00:49:17.360
that Maureen and Rebecca were
talking about due to the ice

00:49:17.360 --> 00:49:18.760
changes in the North.

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:21.774
And you see the ocean in the
South is not doing a lot.

00:49:21.774 --> 00:49:23.190
There's a lot of
ocean down there.

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.780
Water has a lot
of heat capacity.

00:49:25.780 --> 00:49:27.240
What's creating climate change?

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:30.080
Greenhouse gases mainly.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:33.640
This is the big
elephant in the room.

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:35.980
And they are the dominant
cause of observed warming.

00:49:35.980 --> 00:49:38.520
There's other ways--
very complicated subject,

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:40.750
but this is the big part of it.

00:49:40.750 --> 00:49:43.730
And the largest
contribution is CO2.

00:49:43.730 --> 00:49:47.487
And this is the Keeling
curve last night, 401.

00:49:47.487 --> 00:49:49.070
We're actually at
the low for the year

00:49:49.070 --> 00:49:52.190
because we're at the end of
the northern hemisphere summer.

00:49:52.190 --> 00:49:55.420
This is measured at
the top of Mauna Loa.

00:49:55.420 --> 00:49:59.020
Dave Keeling set this
up in the International

00:49:59.020 --> 00:50:01.660
Geophysical Year, 1957.

00:50:01.660 --> 00:50:05.110
And with dogged
persistence, kept it going.

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:09.070
And now it's recognized as
our really amazing record.

00:50:09.070 --> 00:50:12.060
You see the planet
breathing, and the summertime

00:50:12.060 --> 00:50:13.980
and wintertime,
summertime and wintertime.

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:15.660
And relentlessly going up.

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:17.570
And that's the tail at
the end of the curve

00:50:17.570 --> 00:50:19.310
that Maureen showed.

00:50:19.310 --> 00:50:21.130
What happens with
the greenhouse gases?

00:50:21.130 --> 00:50:23.430
We get lots of stuff
happening, bad stuff.

00:50:23.430 --> 00:50:24.695
Well, different stuff.

00:50:24.695 --> 00:50:27.040
It depends on whether
it's good or bad.

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:29.220
Warming-- atmosphere and ocean.

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:30.110
We melt the ice.

00:50:30.110 --> 00:50:31.680
We melt the ice sheets.

00:50:31.680 --> 00:50:33.480
We raise sea level.

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:36.880
We do change the
hydrological cycle.

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:39.850
We're going to change the
patterns of drought and floods.

00:50:39.850 --> 00:50:42.330
Not the patterns, but the
strength of drought and floods.

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:44.000
We have more extreme events.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:47.770
You can't attribute any given
storm to global warming,

00:50:47.770 --> 00:50:52.090
but you can attribute years
of changes in extreme events.

00:50:52.090 --> 00:50:55.900
Ocean acidification is another
important one for the ocean.

00:50:55.900 --> 00:50:59.080
So looking at the ocean,
how does the ocean

00:50:59.080 --> 00:51:02.330
participate in each
of these parts of it?

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:04.640
In carbon-- just
one or two slides--

00:51:04.640 --> 00:51:07.870
heat, and ice, just a
little bit, sea level rise,

00:51:07.870 --> 00:51:10.910
and the water cycle.

00:51:10.910 --> 00:51:14.010
So a statement from
the IPCC-- the ocean

00:51:14.010 --> 00:51:17.920
has absorbed about 30% of the
emitted anthropogenic carbon

00:51:17.920 --> 00:51:19.180
dioxide.

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:21.890
OK, that's an important number.

00:51:21.890 --> 00:51:24.810
You put a certain amount of
carbon up in the-- you burn it.

00:51:24.810 --> 00:51:28.000
It's coming from fossil--
it's fossil fuel burning.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:31.040
8% land, 92%
percent fossil fuel.

00:51:31.040 --> 00:51:34.370
Fossil fuel burning
into the atmosphere.

00:51:34.370 --> 00:51:39.400
A third stays up there, a third
goes into fertilizing the land,

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:41.030
and a third goes into the ocean.

00:51:41.030 --> 00:51:43.180
And the ocean is not going
to sit there and soak up

00:51:43.180 --> 00:51:45.830
the next 40%, 50%, 60%.

00:51:45.830 --> 00:51:48.780
This is an equilibrated
sort of system.

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:50.980
And once it's there, it's there.

00:51:50.980 --> 00:51:54.720
Maureen showed a nice
graph showing that we're

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:56.100
in a commitment phase.

00:51:56.100 --> 00:51:58.070
You put the CO2
in the atmosphere.

00:51:58.070 --> 00:52:00.420
It's not going anywhere.

00:52:00.420 --> 00:52:04.120
A third goes into the ocean
of the part that goes up.

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:05.240
How do you get it out?

00:52:05.240 --> 00:52:08.790
Well, you have to stop
burning it to keep it flat.

00:52:08.790 --> 00:52:11.170
And then maybe you need
to start removing it.

00:52:11.170 --> 00:52:13.910
Here's the other CO2 problem.

00:52:13.910 --> 00:52:16.230
The ocean is 70% of
the Earth's surface.

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:18.460
That CO2, 30% that
goes into the ocean,

00:52:18.460 --> 00:52:22.890
it's not a garbage dump that
you just put in the backyard.

00:52:22.890 --> 00:52:25.290
It goes in and it
affects the marine life.

00:52:25.290 --> 00:52:26.570
So you get acidification.

00:52:26.570 --> 00:52:31.006
Carbonic acid is formed when
you dissolve CO2 into water.

00:52:31.006 --> 00:52:33.190
A little bit changes the pH.

00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:37.410
And that excess acid has
important impacts on organisms.

00:52:37.410 --> 00:52:38.770
And there's a pteropod.

00:52:38.770 --> 00:52:39.971
They're kind of in danger.

00:52:39.971 --> 00:52:41.470
They have beautiful
movies of them--

00:52:41.470 --> 00:52:43.840
I didn't bring any
animations-- flittering around.

00:52:43.840 --> 00:52:45.870
The poor pteropods.

00:52:45.870 --> 00:52:47.730
Anyway, coral reefs,
et cetera, you

00:52:47.730 --> 00:52:49.820
may read about all these things.

00:52:49.820 --> 00:52:52.800
And this is going on now.

00:52:52.800 --> 00:52:54.770
And so there are projections
of how the surface

00:52:54.770 --> 00:52:56.690
pH will change in
the ocean, and also

00:52:56.690 --> 00:53:01.340
how the undersaturation,
how much acidification

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:03.830
is impacting the organisms.

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:05.170
That's it for carbon.

00:53:05.170 --> 00:53:07.510
That's an important second
part of the carbon problem,

00:53:07.510 --> 00:53:10.690
if you haven't been kind of
cued into it before though,

00:53:10.690 --> 00:53:15.280
that the oceans are affected
by the extra carbon as well.

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:16.910
Now we go to heat.

00:53:16.910 --> 00:53:17.710
OK.

00:53:17.710 --> 00:53:20.420
So you've heard
this number already,

00:53:20.420 --> 00:53:26.840
that the excess energy in the
system due to anthropogenic

00:53:26.840 --> 00:53:27.520
forcing.

00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:28.790
So this is the excess.

00:53:28.790 --> 00:53:33.280
Not just the heat, but the
excess is more than 90%

00:53:33.280 --> 00:53:34.180
of what's in there.

00:53:34.180 --> 00:53:38.220
So yay, the ocean is
really helping us out.

00:53:38.220 --> 00:53:41.530
If that were in the atmosphere,
think of how warm we would be.

00:53:41.530 --> 00:53:42.990
And I'll show a graph.

00:53:42.990 --> 00:53:44.630
How do we know these things?

00:53:44.630 --> 00:53:48.110
So this is where we
get to what I do.

00:53:48.110 --> 00:53:50.146
We go out to sea and
make measurements.

00:53:50.146 --> 00:53:51.520
How do we know
where the heat is?

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:52.710
We measure it.

00:53:52.710 --> 00:53:56.370
This is the latest--
yesterday's, maybe today,

00:53:56.370 --> 00:54:01.790
yesterday-- map of where we
have had ocean temperature

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:04.510
and salinity profiles
over the last month.

00:54:04.510 --> 00:54:06.330
So we have a global network now.

00:54:06.330 --> 00:54:08.650
It's been a
phenomenal community,

00:54:08.650 --> 00:54:10.080
international effort.

00:54:10.080 --> 00:54:12.810
Technology was invented
at Scripps by Russ Davis.

00:54:12.810 --> 00:54:14.640
Dean Roemmich at
Scripps has been

00:54:14.640 --> 00:54:16.900
instrumental in taking
this to the world.

00:54:16.900 --> 00:54:18.750
Taking the instruments
to the world.

00:54:18.750 --> 00:54:21.140
This is our network
for the ocean.

00:54:21.140 --> 00:54:23.770
It's the upper 2,000
meters of the ocean.

00:54:23.770 --> 00:54:26.700
That is a picture
of a float that we

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:31.920
were putting out off of a ship
in the Indian Ocean last year.

00:54:31.920 --> 00:54:33.400
Here's what you get from it.

00:54:33.400 --> 00:54:35.160
Is the ocean
temperature changing?

00:54:35.160 --> 00:54:36.270
Yeah, it is.

00:54:36.270 --> 00:54:38.880
This is the change
in heat content

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:43.240
in the upper part of the
ocean-- 700 meters times three,

00:54:43.240 --> 00:54:46.160
2,000 feet-- since 1950.

00:54:46.160 --> 00:54:47.430
Mostly red.

00:54:47.430 --> 00:54:48.380
Oh, OK.

00:54:48.380 --> 00:54:51.120
And then there's a lot of really
interesting structure to it

00:54:51.120 --> 00:54:54.230
that we could spend days
and months discussing.

00:54:54.230 --> 00:54:55.360
But it's mostly red.

00:54:55.360 --> 00:54:56.870
It's pretty patchy,
because we're

00:54:56.870 --> 00:54:59.190
using measurements since 1950.

00:54:59.190 --> 00:55:04.120
So it's ship measurements
in addition to these floats.

00:55:04.120 --> 00:55:07.730
And then-- I'm in the middle
of that one-- we go out to sea

00:55:07.730 --> 00:55:10.480
and we measure to get the rest
of the ocean to the bottom,

00:55:10.480 --> 00:55:12.580
to see how it's changing
over the decades.

00:55:12.580 --> 00:55:15.350
And we make extremely
accurate measurements.

00:55:15.350 --> 00:55:20.100
And here's a map from Sarah
Purkey and Greg Johnson.

00:55:20.100 --> 00:55:22.900
How to make your thesis
become a classic--

00:55:22.900 --> 00:55:26.050
you get 10,000 citations.

00:55:26.050 --> 00:55:28.200
This is the map.

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:32.590
This is using our very precise--
very accurate-- not precise

00:55:32.590 --> 00:55:34.900
but very accurate
deep measurements

00:55:34.900 --> 00:55:38.120
to look at where the warming is
happening below 4,000 meters.

00:55:38.120 --> 00:55:39.950
And you see it's a
very different pattern.

00:55:39.950 --> 00:55:41.500
This is a big eye opener.

00:55:41.500 --> 00:55:43.130
It's very much in the South.

00:55:43.130 --> 00:55:46.170
And this is where a deep
water forms around Antarctica

00:55:46.170 --> 00:55:47.530
and goes to the bottom.

00:55:47.530 --> 00:55:49.160
And the balance is changing.

00:55:49.160 --> 00:55:53.480
And essentially, the deep water
is changing in properties.

00:55:53.480 --> 00:55:55.120
There's less of it.

00:55:55.120 --> 00:55:57.950
And that makes the
deep ocean warm.

00:55:57.950 --> 00:56:00.800
So we have a lot of
interesting observations,

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:03.060
a lot of interesting
things to think about.

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:06.500
This is our take home
graph on warming.

00:56:06.500 --> 00:56:09.870
There's the title, "Global
warming is ocean warming."

00:56:09.870 --> 00:56:12.262
And there is our-- let's
see, is there a pointer here?

00:56:12.262 --> 00:56:13.220
Yes, there's a pointer.

00:56:13.220 --> 00:56:14.820
I'm going to show this.

00:56:14.820 --> 00:56:15.410
Here we go.

00:56:15.410 --> 00:56:21.780
OK, this is the total heat in
the whole system, everything.

00:56:21.780 --> 00:56:24.330
So this is not
just anthropogenic.

00:56:24.330 --> 00:56:25.550
This is it.

00:56:25.550 --> 00:56:28.680
There's some funny units
over here, zettajoules.

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:32.490
This is years since we've had
enough measurements to do this.

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:34.330
There's the total.

00:56:34.330 --> 00:56:38.310
OK, down here, there's a
little tiny purple line.

00:56:38.310 --> 00:56:40.686
That's the atmosphere.

00:56:40.686 --> 00:56:42.310
That's how much the
atmosphere is warm.

00:56:42.310 --> 00:56:47.700
So there was huge press
[INAUDIBLE] about the hiatus.

00:56:47.700 --> 00:56:50.110
Anybody heard of the
hiatus out there?

00:56:50.110 --> 00:56:51.750
There's a lot of skepticism.

00:56:51.750 --> 00:56:54.890
Well, the skeptics could say,
oh, the climate's not changing,

00:56:54.890 --> 00:56:57.370
because look, it's flat
for the last 10 years.

00:56:57.370 --> 00:57:00.380
Well, that was flat in
this curve down here.

00:57:00.380 --> 00:57:02.100
Is it flat in that one?

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:03.720
Oh, no.

00:57:03.720 --> 00:57:04.750
What is this?

00:57:04.750 --> 00:57:08.400
This is the upper ocean, the
upper 700 meters of the ocean.

00:57:08.400 --> 00:57:11.240
This is the deep ocean,
below 700 meters.

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:13.930
You see, this is the
93% we're talking about.

00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:15.210
There's bumps and wiggles.

00:57:15.210 --> 00:57:17.750
Yes, there's
climate variability,

00:57:17.750 --> 00:57:21.050
but there's a relentless
upward swing there.

00:57:21.050 --> 00:57:24.590
And most of the heat is in
the ocean, thank goodness.

00:57:24.590 --> 00:57:26.550
But it also means
that's what's happening.

00:57:26.550 --> 00:57:29.740
When we have these bumps
and wiggles in our surface

00:57:29.740 --> 00:57:32.800
temperature, hiatus, et
cetera, what's happening

00:57:32.800 --> 00:57:35.414
is there's an exchange between
the ocean and the atmosphere.

00:57:35.414 --> 00:57:37.330
And the ocean is sitting
there going, yeah OK,

00:57:37.330 --> 00:57:38.500
let's have a mode.

00:57:38.500 --> 00:57:40.750
And let's take up some heat
and change the temperature

00:57:40.750 --> 00:57:41.830
at the surface.

00:57:41.830 --> 00:57:46.260
But the heat in the
whole system is going up.

00:57:46.260 --> 00:57:47.720
What's this doing?

00:57:47.720 --> 00:57:49.900
Overall, the heating
of the whole system.

00:57:49.900 --> 00:57:50.910
There's the ice.

00:57:50.910 --> 00:57:53.490
The Greenland and Antarctic
ice sheets are losing mass.

00:57:53.490 --> 00:57:55.580
Glaciers are continuing
to shrink worldwide.

00:57:55.580 --> 00:57:59.120
That's not the ocean
so I'm not showing it.

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:00.330
Arctic sea ice, et cetera.

00:58:00.330 --> 00:58:02.650
And the Antarctic sea
ice has expanded, which

00:58:02.650 --> 00:58:04.150
is very interesting topic.

00:58:04.150 --> 00:58:06.300
And there's workshops
going on about that.

00:58:06.300 --> 00:58:10.430
That's attributable
to-- the largest

00:58:10.430 --> 00:58:13.510
extent is in the winter when
there's no ice albedo feedback.

00:58:13.510 --> 00:58:15.150
It's dark down there.

00:58:15.150 --> 00:58:18.200
And the wind is blowing stronger
because of global warming.

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:20.730
And the wind pushes the ice out.

00:58:20.730 --> 00:58:21.900
So the cover is going up.

00:58:21.900 --> 00:58:25.180
We've already seen these great
pictures of the Arctic ice.

00:58:25.180 --> 00:58:27.910
Here's the ice sheet warming.

00:58:27.910 --> 00:58:32.920
This is Greenland, where
it's warming and losing mass.

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:34.480
There's the mass loss.

00:58:34.480 --> 00:58:36.210
This is Antarctica
where it's warming.

00:58:36.210 --> 00:58:37.294
Here's the mass loss.

00:58:37.294 --> 00:58:38.710
You note it's not
the whole thing.

00:58:38.710 --> 00:58:42.050
So yeah, we're going to be
kind of happy with only--

00:58:42.050 --> 00:58:43.840
how many meters was that?

00:58:43.840 --> 00:58:44.340
- Six.

00:58:44.340 --> 00:58:49.590
- Six meters, as opposed to 180.

00:58:49.590 --> 00:58:51.670
Six meters of ice loss.

00:58:51.670 --> 00:58:53.670
As an oceanographer,
we're interested in this.

00:58:53.670 --> 00:58:57.470
You've already seen from
Rebecca and from Maureen

00:58:57.470 --> 00:59:02.290
how the ocean affects
the ice balance.

