01:11:19.130 --> 01:11:23.200
In Antarctica, the ice
expanded, but it was only

01:11:23.200 --> 01:11:26.320
able to expand out to the end
of the Arctic ice shelf, which

01:11:26.320 --> 01:11:29.640
was more exposed because of
the sea level drop because

01:11:29.640 --> 01:11:31.340
of the Northern
hemisphere ice sheet.

01:11:31.340 --> 01:11:33.720
But then it just falls off
the continent and flows away.

01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:35.820
So it really is--
there's no land for it

01:11:35.820 --> 01:11:37.830
to move northward onto.

01:11:37.830 --> 01:11:41.200
It's limited by the size
of the Antarctic continent.

01:11:41.200 --> 01:11:44.290
- So I have another
question about what

01:11:44.290 --> 01:11:47.250
oceanographers call the
meridional overturning

01:11:47.250 --> 01:11:48.210
circulation.

01:11:48.210 --> 01:11:52.110
So the oceans transport heat
from the tropics to the poles.

01:11:52.110 --> 01:11:55.970
And there's been a
lot of papers that

01:11:55.970 --> 01:12:00.070
came out about the strength of
this overturning circulation.

01:12:00.070 --> 01:12:03.880
From the paleo literature,
we know that in the past,

01:12:03.880 --> 01:12:06.720
the strength of the
circulation has changed.

01:12:06.720 --> 01:12:09.760
And so what is our
current thinking?

01:12:09.760 --> 01:12:14.090
If we melt sea ice and we put
all this fresh water up there

01:12:14.090 --> 01:12:16.650
at the poles, do we
think that's going

01:12:16.650 --> 01:12:18.490
to change the rate of
deep water formation

01:12:18.490 --> 01:12:21.400
and the overturning rate?

01:12:21.400 --> 01:12:23.340
Do we have any clues
from the past that--

01:12:25.900 --> 01:12:28.150
- Well, you could probably
better speak to the future.

01:12:28.150 --> 01:12:28.850
- I could speculate.

01:12:28.850 --> 01:12:30.433
- It's certainly
happened in the past.

01:12:30.433 --> 01:12:31.440
- That it shutdown?

01:12:31.440 --> 01:12:34.410
- Yeah, major reorganization
of ocean currents.

01:12:34.410 --> 01:12:35.880
- So maybe you can
tell us what you

01:12:35.880 --> 01:12:38.060
think is happening, or
might happen in the future.

01:12:38.060 --> 01:12:39.360
And then Maureen can tell us--

01:12:39.360 --> 01:12:41.260
- And then somebody
else out there

01:12:41.260 --> 01:12:43.190
can come up with a
very different answer.

01:12:43.190 --> 01:12:45.740
This is pure
speculation in a sense.

01:12:45.740 --> 01:12:46.490
Three sides there.

01:12:46.490 --> 01:12:48.910
What really regulates-- OK,
what we're talking about here

01:12:48.910 --> 01:12:50.670
is the overturning circulation.

01:12:50.670 --> 01:12:53.410
You saw that warm water
on Rebecca's slides going

01:12:53.410 --> 01:12:55.350
all the way up into the Arctic.

01:12:55.350 --> 01:12:57.470
That is part of the
overturning circulation.

01:12:57.470 --> 01:12:59.320
That water is going
all the way up there,

01:12:59.320 --> 01:13:02.890
and it's getting cold and
sinking, and coming out.

01:13:02.890 --> 01:13:05.795
So that's the North Atlantic
part of the overturn.

01:13:08.440 --> 01:13:12.960
That progression of
warm water up there

01:13:12.960 --> 01:13:15.690
is important in
keeping passages open.

01:13:15.690 --> 01:13:20.220
It's part of the Western
European warming.

01:13:20.220 --> 01:13:22.630
That part-- OK, that's one part.

01:13:22.630 --> 01:13:24.900
And the Southern Ocean
is the other cold part

01:13:24.900 --> 01:13:29.530
of the world, is isolated
by the circumpolar current.

01:13:29.530 --> 01:13:31.040
And we have a lot
of ice formation

01:13:31.040 --> 01:13:32.040
right around Antarctica.

01:13:32.040 --> 01:13:34.340
It makes very dense water
that goes to the bottom.

01:13:34.340 --> 01:13:35.870
So we have these two sources.

01:13:35.870 --> 01:13:39.140
We have one northern
hemisphere, high latitude source

01:13:39.140 --> 01:13:43.130
that does not make deep water,
which is the Pacific Ocean.

01:13:43.130 --> 01:13:47.830
And it's our current experiment
in how salt, or lack of salt,

01:13:47.830 --> 01:13:49.960
shuts down overturn.

01:13:49.960 --> 01:13:53.050
So the contrast between the
Pacific and the Atlantic

01:13:53.050 --> 01:13:56.730
is the Pacific has a lot
of rain and is very fresh,

01:13:56.730 --> 01:13:59.760
and the Atlantic has a lot
of evaporation so it's salty.

01:13:59.760 --> 01:14:02.850
So you put these two things
at both ends of your table

01:14:02.850 --> 01:14:05.880
and you say, which one wins if
you cool them both to freezing?

01:14:05.880 --> 01:14:08.830
Oh, the salty water will get
dense and the fresh water

01:14:08.830 --> 01:14:11.940
will just float on
that salty dense water.

01:14:11.940 --> 01:14:14.120
So that's the simple
picture set up

01:14:14.120 --> 01:14:16.810
by [? Stommel ?] and
earlier, a long time ago,

01:14:16.810 --> 01:14:18.390
we have these two ends.

01:14:18.390 --> 01:14:22.720
And that balance
only changes overall

01:14:22.720 --> 01:14:26.620
when you move the continents.

01:14:26.620 --> 01:14:28.740
That's tectonics.

01:14:28.740 --> 01:14:31.250
So then the question is,
what's the vigor of those two

01:14:31.250 --> 01:14:31.990
overturns?

01:14:31.990 --> 01:14:36.030
The Pacific one is
weak, it's shallow.

01:14:36.030 --> 01:14:38.750
The Atlantic one is
10 times stronger

01:14:38.750 --> 01:14:41.000
and goes to the ocean bottom.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:43.320
The question is if you
add a lot of fresh water

01:14:43.320 --> 01:14:46.610
from all this melting ice on
top of the North Atlantic,

01:14:46.610 --> 01:14:49.220
does it shut that
circulation down, and then

01:14:49.220 --> 01:14:52.660
change the amount of
warm water moving north?

01:14:52.660 --> 01:14:56.390
And so we had hints that
all this fresh water

01:14:56.390 --> 01:14:59.900
was starting to weaken
things a decade or two ago.

01:14:59.900 --> 01:15:03.080
The Northern North Atlantic
was relentlessly freshening.

01:15:03.080 --> 01:15:04.680
But it turned around.

01:15:04.680 --> 01:15:06.450
And some of us went, ha ha.

01:15:06.450 --> 01:15:08.590
The circulation
finally caught up.

01:15:08.590 --> 01:15:12.080
All that extra evaporation
down off of here,

01:15:12.080 --> 01:15:15.190
off of the Gulf Stream
over to Europe and Africa,

01:15:15.190 --> 01:15:17.880
the extra evaporation
makes salty water

01:15:17.880 --> 01:15:22.420
that got pulled north and
helped keep that cranking.

01:15:22.420 --> 01:15:27.140
So my speculation is that,
yeah, the whole thing warms up.

01:15:27.140 --> 01:15:29.220
It becomes more stratified.

01:15:29.220 --> 01:15:31.880
You're dumping more
fresh water in the north,

01:15:31.880 --> 01:15:35.120
but you're also pushing
all this salty water in.

01:15:35.120 --> 01:15:36.540
So you've got to have a balance.

01:15:36.540 --> 01:15:38.123
And I don't know
which way the balance

01:15:38.123 --> 01:15:40.480
will go in the next 100 years.

01:15:40.480 --> 01:15:43.000
You need to run a lot
of models to do that.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:45.684
Maybe some of you have
done that already.

01:15:45.684 --> 01:15:46.350
- OK, thank you.

01:15:46.350 --> 01:15:47.530
I'm going to pass
it to the audience,

01:15:47.530 --> 01:15:48.840
because we have
quite some questions.

01:15:48.840 --> 01:15:50.830
So please say your name
and introduce yourself.

01:15:50.830 --> 01:15:54.815
- My name's John Wigglesworth
and I'm a secondary school

01:15:54.815 --> 01:15:56.490
Earth science teacher.

01:15:56.490 --> 01:16:00.580
And I spent a semester teaching
about oceans and climate.

01:16:00.580 --> 01:16:02.360
And I wondered if
you had any thoughts

01:16:02.360 --> 01:16:05.550
on how to give your
message in a way that

01:16:05.550 --> 01:16:07.640
gives young kids some hope.

01:16:07.640 --> 01:16:11.720
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:11.720 --> 01:16:14.660
It's something that I deal
with all the time working

01:16:14.660 --> 01:16:16.940
with eighth graders and
juniors in high school.

01:16:16.940 --> 01:16:20.690
And it's a pretty
sobering message.

01:16:20.690 --> 01:16:24.620
And how do you do it that
gives people a sense of hope?

01:16:24.620 --> 01:16:26.600
- I'm happy to try
to answer that.

01:16:26.600 --> 01:16:29.800
So I'm actually
extremely optimistic,

01:16:29.800 --> 01:16:31.690
even though it's a very
pessimistic message,

01:16:31.690 --> 01:16:35.190
just because I firmly believe
that the limits of-- there

01:16:35.190 --> 01:16:41.070
is no limit to human creativity
and our ability to engineer

01:16:41.070 --> 01:16:44.050
our way out of this.

01:16:44.050 --> 01:16:46.520
But it has to start
with the acknowledgement

01:16:46.520 --> 01:16:51.570
of the problem and an effort
to reduce CO2 emissions.

01:16:51.570 --> 01:16:55.600
So I'm not sure,
but I think people

01:16:55.600 --> 01:16:57.600
have to be empowered by
knowledge of the problem

01:16:57.600 --> 01:16:59.980
and want to solve it.

01:16:59.980 --> 01:17:02.320
- So I would add to that--
I struggle with this too.

01:17:02.320 --> 01:17:04.010
I teach a class on the Arctic.

01:17:04.010 --> 01:17:06.440
And you come to the end,
you think, how can I

01:17:06.440 --> 01:17:08.130
end on some positive note?

01:17:08.130 --> 01:17:12.500
And I think it's to remember
in that that we do have

01:17:12.500 --> 01:17:14.460
the ability to change this.

01:17:14.460 --> 01:17:14.960
Right?

01:17:14.960 --> 01:17:15.760
If we go out there
and see, we're

01:17:15.760 --> 01:17:17.384
going to throw all
the money that we're

01:17:17.384 --> 01:17:20.800
putting into making ourselves
rich into solving this problem,

01:17:20.800 --> 01:17:22.010
we can do it.

01:17:22.010 --> 01:17:24.490
Perhaps the most positive thing
I saw in this was somebody

01:17:24.490 --> 01:17:26.780
said, right, I know
seven technologies that

01:17:26.780 --> 01:17:29.730
could chip away at a
seventh of this problem,

01:17:29.730 --> 01:17:31.630
of the CO2 problem.

01:17:31.630 --> 01:17:35.362
But we have to teach the
people that this is happening,

01:17:35.362 --> 01:17:37.945
that we have to face up to it,
like we teach people to face up

01:17:37.945 --> 01:17:39.084
to problems in life.

01:17:39.084 --> 01:17:40.750
And go in and do it,
and find on the way

01:17:40.750 --> 01:17:43.420
some way of predicting
and mitigating it.

01:17:43.420 --> 01:17:45.370
So it's their future.

01:17:45.370 --> 01:17:48.930
And I hope we can get them
to grasp it and do something

01:17:48.930 --> 01:17:49.430
about it.

01:17:49.430 --> 01:17:51.650
And not just blame
it all on our watch.

01:17:51.650 --> 01:17:53.290
- And I think
something we can add

01:17:53.290 --> 01:17:55.880
is that there have been other
problems for which there was

01:17:55.880 --> 01:17:58.420
no political will in
the past, but when

01:17:58.420 --> 01:18:02.530
public opinion changed,
political will came about.

01:18:02.530 --> 01:18:05.210
So I think there's
hope for that too.

01:18:05.210 --> 01:18:06.520
- So take the CFC ban.

01:18:06.520 --> 01:18:09.840
We managed to ban CFCs, because
that was a science problem.

01:18:09.840 --> 01:18:11.530
So we can do it.

01:18:11.530 --> 01:18:15.021
We just have to team
together and actually do it.

01:18:15.021 --> 01:18:15.520
- OK.

01:18:15.520 --> 01:18:16.750
So the next question.

01:18:16.750 --> 01:18:18.875
We're going to have to be
a little quick because we

01:18:18.875 --> 01:18:19.640
have five minutes.

01:18:19.640 --> 01:18:21.020
- I'm Christina Hernandez.

01:18:21.020 --> 01:18:23.680
I'm a graduate student
in the MIT/WHOI Joint

01:18:23.680 --> 01:18:25.440
Program in Oceanography.

01:18:25.440 --> 01:18:29.610
And I had a question for Rebecca
about sort of ice edge blooms

01:18:29.610 --> 01:18:33.390
and the effect of melt
ponds on under ice blooms.

01:18:33.390 --> 01:18:37.130
And so I was wondering
if ocean color changes,

01:18:37.130 --> 01:18:40.350
whether those blooms happen
under the ice during melt ponds

01:18:40.350 --> 01:18:43.070
or at the edges,
if that contributes

01:18:43.070 --> 01:18:45.840
at all to these positive
feedbacks that melt the ice.

01:18:45.840 --> 01:18:47.930
Like do you know anything
about [INAUDIBLE]?

01:18:47.930 --> 01:18:49.320
- So this is really cool.

01:18:49.320 --> 01:18:51.570
So the idea is if you're
going to have a phytoplankton

01:18:51.570 --> 01:18:54.410
bloom in the ocean, you need to
have nutrients, stratification,

01:18:54.410 --> 01:18:55.470
and light.

01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:57.530
If we get melt
ponds in the ice, we

01:18:57.530 --> 01:19:00.680
get windows in the ocean
which are allowing light

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:03.250
to come into under the ice
regions, which we always

01:19:03.250 --> 01:19:07.200
thought were devoid of life
until the ice had melted.

01:19:07.200 --> 01:19:09.990
We're finding there are
those blooms in some places.

01:19:09.990 --> 01:19:11.932
Quite why, we don't know.

01:19:11.932 --> 01:19:13.390
We think because
of the melt ponds,

01:19:13.390 --> 01:19:15.020
have they always been there?

01:19:15.020 --> 01:19:15.770
We don't know.

01:19:15.770 --> 01:19:18.380
What is the feedback then
from that phytoplankton

01:19:18.380 --> 01:19:21.120
trapping more energy
into the ocean?

01:19:21.120 --> 01:19:23.401
Some-- don't quite know.

01:19:23.401 --> 01:19:24.650
We're kind of working on that.

01:19:24.650 --> 01:19:26.140
Amala and I are working
on that at the minute.

01:19:26.140 --> 01:19:27.140
So we can talk off line.

01:19:27.140 --> 01:19:29.390
That's really exciting.

01:19:29.390 --> 01:19:32.290
- My name is Tim Johnson
and I'm a software engineer.

01:19:32.290 --> 01:19:35.030
And I have one, I
guess, a futuristic kind

01:19:35.030 --> 01:19:37.600
of question, in that it
sounds like we're heading

01:19:37.600 --> 01:19:38.840
for sort of an alien world.

01:19:38.840 --> 01:19:40.380
We don't have to travel
to another planet

01:19:40.380 --> 01:19:41.240
to find an alien world.

01:19:41.240 --> 01:19:42.680
We're going to get
one right here.

01:19:42.680 --> 01:19:44.340
I met that somebody
was from Kuwait,

01:19:44.340 --> 01:19:46.680
and he said it's 140
degrees Fahrenheit there

01:19:46.680 --> 01:19:48.140
and it's getting hotter.

01:19:48.140 --> 01:19:50.900
And to me, that
seems pretty alien.

01:19:50.900 --> 01:19:53.270
And it seems to me
that we almost can't

01:19:53.270 --> 01:19:54.500
stop what you're describing.

01:19:54.500 --> 01:19:57.310
Even if we became much
more politically active

01:19:57.310 --> 01:20:00.181
and the Republicans suddenly
became totally different,

01:20:00.181 --> 01:20:01.930
we're still not going
to change very fast.

01:20:01.930 --> 01:20:05.040
Even if they changed it
tomorrow, passing legislation,

01:20:05.040 --> 01:20:06.030
changing things.

01:20:06.030 --> 01:20:08.530
And so it seems to me we
have almost a whole new area

01:20:08.530 --> 01:20:10.410
of science of how to
deal with the fact

01:20:10.410 --> 01:20:13.320
when the world is going to
change over the next century,

01:20:13.320 --> 01:20:15.120
because it really is.

01:20:15.120 --> 01:20:17.290
Is this sort of something
people are thinking about,

01:20:17.290 --> 01:20:19.415
like most businesses are
looking how to make money?

01:20:19.415 --> 01:20:21.010
Like you can have
tours taking you

01:20:21.010 --> 01:20:23.720
through the Northwest Passage
which didn't exist before.

01:20:23.720 --> 01:20:26.247
But it seems like a
sort of a big area.

01:20:26.247 --> 01:20:28.455
I suppose it's a way to make
a lot of money for some.

01:20:28.455 --> 01:20:31.460
That may encourage some
Republicans to do it.

01:20:31.460 --> 01:20:34.830
- There is a big burgeoning
of renewable energy.

01:20:34.830 --> 01:20:36.420
And you can see it
around the world.

01:20:36.420 --> 01:20:40.600
And Europe is just
going bonk-- it's great.

01:20:40.600 --> 01:20:41.470
It's the future.

01:20:41.470 --> 01:20:45.230
And the US is going that
direction too, slowly.

01:20:45.230 --> 01:20:50.410
There's a whole area of
adaptation and engineering

01:20:50.410 --> 01:20:52.570
that is very active.

01:20:52.570 --> 01:20:56.430
So encourage your students
to go and work in that.

01:20:56.430 --> 01:20:58.440
But don't eliminate
the basic science,

01:20:58.440 --> 01:21:01.170
as the Australian government
did for a brief period

01:21:01.170 --> 01:21:02.280
the last year.

01:21:02.280 --> 01:21:04.060
They said oh, we
know the answer.

01:21:04.060 --> 01:21:05.010
Climate is changing.

01:21:05.010 --> 01:21:07.460
We don't need you guys anymore.

01:21:07.460 --> 01:21:10.200
Let's put all our money
into making some money

01:21:10.200 --> 01:21:13.010
on adaptation and engineering.

01:21:13.010 --> 01:21:15.700
And there was a big kerfuffle,
because when you have cancer

01:21:15.700 --> 01:21:17.385
you don't stop taking
your temperature

01:21:17.385 --> 01:21:18.760
because you know
you have cancer.

01:21:21.840 --> 01:21:23.860
So we have to have
both legs of that.

01:21:23.860 --> 01:21:25.510
We don't represent
that end here,

01:21:25.510 --> 01:21:28.100
but maybe some other
people can speak to that.

01:21:28.100 --> 01:21:29.300
It's very active.

01:21:29.300 --> 01:21:31.910
There are some
geoengineering ideas out

01:21:31.910 --> 01:21:35.355
there-- scrubbing the
atmosphere, clean up your mess.

01:21:35.355 --> 01:21:36.730
- So if I could
just add to that.

01:21:36.730 --> 01:21:40.060
Portugal, I think, ran
entirely on renewable energy

01:21:40.060 --> 01:21:42.590
for a period of time
this last summer.

01:21:42.590 --> 01:21:43.290
OK?

01:21:43.290 --> 01:21:44.920
So it can be done.

01:21:44.920 --> 01:21:47.600
We just have to decide
we don't just want money,

01:21:47.600 --> 01:21:50.280
we want a world for our
children, as they say.

01:21:50.280 --> 01:21:51.462
- OK, thank you very much.

01:21:51.462 --> 01:21:52.670
Thank you all for being here.

01:21:52.670 --> 01:21:53.503
And of course, John.

01:21:53.503 --> 01:21:54.660
- Thanks to the panel.

